The United States had threatened to take retaliatory action within a month, All last week, the Posts and Telecommunications Ministry published proposals in the Japanese press to resolve the dispute, which has deeply divided the Japanese bureaucracy.

abstract: LEAD: An important vote of the 2,105 United States partners of Ernst & Whinney and Arthur Young that ended yesterday cleared the way for a merger of the two accounting firms.

abstract: LEAD: Moving to overcome a series of recent defections, Kidder, Peabody & Company yesterday named Scott C. Newquist as the head of investment banking, effective on June 1.

abstract: LEAD: A train derailed and plunged over a cliff in western Kenya today, killing at least 11 people and injuring 114, many seriously, the Kenya News Agency reported. The train was carrying 800 passengers when it jumped the tracks at Londiani, 150 miles northwest of Nairobi.

Rothmeier, chairman and chief executive of NWA.

abstract: LEAD: * American Express Bank Ltd., the banking subsidiary of American Express, named Marc S. Shoenfeld executive vice president and chief financial officer.

headline: Economic Calendar
abstract: LEAD: Listed below are the major economic indicators scheduled to be released this week.  Monday   None  Tuesday   Durable Goods ... April  Wednesday   None  Thursday   G.N.P. ... 1st Qtr.   Corporate Profits ... 1st Qtr.  Friday   Personal Income ... April

headline: Jews Stalk Arabs After Israeli's Death
abstract: LEAD: For the second time in less than a week, angry Israelis roamed the streets on Sunday night and again this morning, shouting ''Death to Arabs!'' as they looked for Palestinians they could lynch, this time in retaliation for the death of a soldier whose body was found on Sunday with a bullet to the head.

headline: A Student's Body Is Honored With Tears of Horror and Cries for Revenge
abstract: LEAD: For the dozen student pallbearers who walked solemnly into the university hall, it was a grim scene: The body of a friend lay wrapped in a red cloth and nestled in a bed of ice on a table.

headline: Be Adventurous, Executives Tell The Class of 1989
abstract: LEAD: They say that everything has its cycle. So, too, with advice.

headline: New Jersey's Gasoline Rule
abstract: LEAD: The Environmental Protection Agency today gave New Jersey permission to put into effect new rules on the formulation of gasoline, in an effort to cut smog.

headline: Company News; Chinese Buying VW Equipment
abstract: LEAD: Volkswagen A.G. said it would sell the tooling and production equipment from its closed New Stanton, Pa., plant to First Automobile Works of Changchun, China. A VW spokesman, Tom McDonald, declined to put a dollar value on the transaction. He said the equipment from the plant would be removed in about four months and would be shipped to China.

headline: The Kabul Capitalist, if Not Capitalism, Thrives
abstract: LEAD: For Kabul's poor, a decade of civil war has brought shortages of food and medical care. But for those with money, it is a world of choice.

headline: Baker Meets With Shamir; Calls Ideas 'Encouraging'
abstract: LEAD: Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel presented his ideas for settling the Arab-Israeli conflict to Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d today, and Mr. Baker said he found the Israeli proposals ''very encouraging.''

headline: 3 Employees Sue Drexel Over Sale
abstract: LEAD: Three employees of the retail brokerage unit of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. filed a class-action lawsuit yesterday against the firm, charging Drexel's top managers with breach of contract and violations of their fiduciary duties because of a plan to sell the division.

headline: Hungary Moves to Abandon Dam Project on the Danube
abstract: LEAD: A Government panel voted today to abandon a dam project on the Danube, calling it ''a symbol of Hungary's mismanaged economic development,'' the official press agency reported.

headline: DOLLAR UP AGAIN, DEFYING EFFORTS OF CENTRAL BANKS
abstract: LEAD: Defying another round of concerted central bank intervention and a strong signal of concern from the White House, the dollar swept past two more milestones yesterday in its relentless advance.

headline: Stock Offering By Weirton Steel
abstract: LEAD: The Weirton Steel Corporation, one of the nation's largest employee-owned companies, went public today by offering four million shares of its common stock for trading on the New York Stock Exchange. The first offering of Weirton Steel stock opened at $14.50 a share. The stock ended the day at $15.125, up 62.5 cents, and was the 10th-most-active issue with more than 1.2 million shares trading.

headline: Afghanistan Is Appointing a Panel for Peace Talks
abstract: LEAD: Under intensifying military pressure, the Soviet-backed Government of President Najibullah announced today that it would appoint a three-member commission to negotiate without conditions to end Afghanistan's 10-year war.

headline: What Acquiring Minds Want to Own
abstract: LEAD: ''ENQUIRER GRASS TO GROW UNWATCHED. GARDENERS REJOICE.''

headline: Mortgage Rates Decline
abstract: LEAD: Fixed-rate home mortgages are averaging 10.99 percent, according to a national survey released Friday by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation. That rate was down from a rate of 11.11 percent in the previous week.

headline: Comsat Net Up 15.4%
abstract: LEAD: The Comsat Corporation said today that its earnings rose 15.4 percent in the first three months of 1989, primarily from growth in its international satellite operations. Net income for the quarter ended March 31 was $16.5 million, or 89 cents a share, on revenues of $97.4 million, compared with earnings of $14.3 million, or 77 cents a share, on revenues of $84.1 million a year ago.

headline: 3M's Profit Up by 14.8%
abstract: LEAD: The Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Company said Thursday that its first-quarter income rose 14.8 percent, to $318 million, or $1.43 a share, from $277 million, or $1.22 a share, a year ago.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Executive Quits Ogilvy Over Job
abstract: LEAD: OGILVY & MATHER WORLDWIDE announced yesterday that Norman C. Berry, creative director of its troubled New York office, as well as worldwide creative director, had resigned from the agency.

headline: Bank Board Sued on Curb
abstract: LEAD: The Great Western Financial Corporation filed suit here today against the Government, challenging a decision that blocked one of the company's savings and loan subsidiaries from leaving the ailing Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation.

headline: Treasury Notes and Bonds Mixed
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds were narrowly mixed yesterday in moderately active trading, as market participants shrugged off a preliminary Government report that showed non-farm economic growth in the first quarter had slowed.

headline: British Soldier Shot to Death In Ulster in Error, Police Say
abstract: LEAD: A 21-year-old British soldier was shot to death today, apparently by a fellow soldier who was firing at a motorist who tried to run one of the soldiers down, the police said.

headline: 20 Die and 100 Are Wounded in Beirut Shelling
abstract: LEAD: More than 30 hours of intense shelling in both sectors of the Lebanese capital left 20 people dead and about 100 others wounded, the police said today.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Bissell to Chiat/Day
abstract: LEAD: Chiat/Day, New York won a $10 million account yesterday from Bissell Inc., a home appliance manufacturer. The agency edged out Lord, Einstein, O'Neill & Partners in the competition for the account, and will create broadcast and print ads for the company. The account had been handled by Chickering & Associates, a small agency in Grand Rapids, Mich., where Bissell is based.

headline: Resignations Over Scandal In Brazil
abstract: LEAD: In the latest repercussions of a widening stock scandal, the president of Brazil's central bank and the head of Rio's stock exchange have announced their resignations.

headline: CORPORATE RAIDER GUILTY ON 9 COUNTS IN WALL ST. FRAUD
abstract: LEAD: Paul A. Bilzerian, the corporate raider and chairman of the Singer Company, was convicted yesterday of nine counts of securities fraud, conspiracy and making false statements to the Government.

headline: Sears and Dai-Ichi
abstract: LEAD: Sears, Roebuck & Company formed a venture with the Dai-Ichi Katei Denki Company, under which the Japanese consumer electronics retailer will import and sell Sears-brand electric appliances in Japan, Dai-Ichi said. Beginning Thursday, Dai-Ichi will sell three types of large Sears refrigerators at its 196 outlets and through direct-mail retailing.

headline: New Inquiry Urged in Killing of 3 on Gibraltar
abstract: LEAD: An independent report today criticized the British Government inquest into the killing of three Irish Republican Army guerrillas by British troops in Gibraltar in March 1988 and said Parliament should appoint a judge empowered to conduct a fuller inquiry.

headline: Palestinian Killed During Riot
abstract: LEAD: Israeli soldiers shot and killed a 20-year-old Palestinian today during a riot at the Amari refugee area in the West Bank, the army and Palestinians said. Officials at Ramallah Hospital said the Palestinian, Ismail Baba, suffered a gunshot wound in the chest and was dead on arrival at the hospital.

headline: Korea-U.S. Trade Gap
abstract: LEAD: South Korea today reported a sharp fall in its trade surplus with the United States in the first quarter, with imports of American goods rising sharply. Trade Ministry officials said the surplus in the first three months of 1989 fell 34 percent, to $1.2 billion, from the period in 1988. South Korean imports from the United States soared 25 percent, to $3.3 billion, while exports to the United States rose only 1 percent, to $4.5 billion, preliminary figures indicate.

headline: Gasoline Prices Post a Sharp Rise
abstract: LEAD: Retail gasoline prices have jumped sharply in the last two weeks, reaching their highest levels in more than three years. Prices at some service stations have gone up by 10 cents a gallon or more, or about 10 percent.

headline: Investment Group Drops V Band Bid
abstract: LEAD: An investment group led by Thomas E. Feil, the chairman of the V Band Corporation, has dropped its proposal to acquire the telephone equipment concern, based in Yonkers. Mr. Feil and KBA Partners L.P., a venture capital concern, had made a proposal to acquire V Band for a price in the range of $9 to $11 a share, for a maximum total purchase price of $57 million.

headline: 80 NATIONS FAVOR BAN TO HELP OZONE
abstract: LEAD: As concern grows that manmade chemicals are destroying the ozone layer in the atmosphere, 80 nations indicated today that they would favor banning production of certain harmful substances by the end of the century.

headline: PRESIDENT WISHES GORBACHEV WELL ON SOVIET CHANGE
abstract: LEAD: In his most positive assessment so far of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policies, President Bush said today that he wanted the economic and political changes to succeed and welcomed recent Soviet arms control proposals.

headline: Sematech Awards 7 Contracts
abstract: LEAD: Sematech, the semiconductor industry's two-year-old consortium for manufacturing research, today awarded its first development contracts to seven companies for advanced equipment and supplies required to produce a new generation of computer chips.

headline: Japan Inquiry Trains Sights On Nakasone
abstract: LEAD: While Japan's political leaders flounder to find a new Prime Minister, investigators are focusing on an old one, putting extraordinary pressure - and the lingering threat of bribery charges - on Yasuhiro Nakasone.

headline: USAir to Buy Up to 40 Planes
abstract: LEAD: In its second important aircraft order within weeks, USAir Group Inc. announced a $1.3 billion deal today with the McDonnell Douglas Corporation to buy 20 MD-82 aircraft and take options on 20 more.

headline: Patents; A Design to Start A Fusion Reaction
abstract: LEAD: Although the excitement over claims of achieving ''cold fusion'' has now subsided into skepticism and disappointment, research continues on older approaches to harnessing the power that fuels the sun.

headline: Concession to Chris-Craft on Warner
abstract: LEAD: In an effort to break a stalemate between two long-feuding executives and get on with an $18 billion merger, Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc. said yesterday that they were willing to concede that Warner had violated a contract with Chris-Craft Industries.

headline: Reagan Gets A Red Carpet From British
abstract: LEAD: Former President Ronald Reagan returned to Britain this week as a private citizen but was welcomed almost as visiting nobility.

headline: Gorbachev, in London, Chides U.S. on Arms Talks
abstract: LEAD: Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the Soviet leader, told Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher today that the Bush Administration's foreign policy review was taking too long and endangering the momentum of negotiations to reduce nuclear arms, a Soviet spokesman said.

headline: Loss Widens At Savings Unit
abstract: LEAD: The Western Savings and Loan Association, which wiped out the equity of its shareholders and fell below regulatory capital guidelines at the end of 1988, reported on Thursday that it had a $99.8 million first-quarter loss. Its loss a year ago was $1.9 million.

headline: Kuwait to Remove U.S. Flag From Two of Its Oil Tankers
abstract: LEAD: Kuwait is about to remove the American flag from 2 of the 11 oil tankers that it registered in the United States at the height of the Iran-Iraq war, diplomats said today.

headline: In Shift, Sweden Dailies Identify Palme Suspect
abstract: LEAD: Ten Swedish newspapers today published the name and picture of the man charged with murdering Prime Minister Olof Palme, defying the Swedish press association's code of ethics, which discourages the publishing of names and pictures of people who have not been convicted.

headline: U.S. Bars Beech-Nut
abstract: LEAD: Eighteen months after it was convicted of selling bogus apple juice to consumers, the Beech-Nut Corporation has been barred from doing any business with the Federal Government through 1991.

headline: In Cuba, Remembering Hemingway
abstract: LEAD: For some, a trip to the Hemingway Museum, a house on the outskirts of Havana, where Ernest Hemingway lived for many years, seemed a strange outing for Raisa Gorbachev, the wife of the Soviet leader.

headline: Salvadoran Rebels Reject New Offer for Talks
abstract: LEAD: Leftist rebels today spurned the new president's proposal for a dialogue, dismissing it as a call to capitulate.

headline: Gateway Talks Are Reported
abstract: LEAD: The Gateway Corporation, a British food retailer that is the target of a hostile $2.9 billion takeover bid from a group of British investors, said today that it had been approached by Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Company, the United States leveraged buyout house.

headline: Coleco Agrees to Sell Its Assets to Hasbro
abstract: LEAD: Coleco Industries, the troubled toy maker, has agreed to sell most of its assets to a rival, Hasbro Industries, for $85 million in cash, the companies announced today.

headline: Wall Street, in a Slump, Rethinks Its Business
abstract: Wall Street, once awash in mega-profits, is now having to cope with a very dry spell.

abstract: LEAD: * Bausch & Lomb Inc., Rochester, an eyewear manufacturer, said it had reached an agreement with Levi Strauss & Co., San Francisco, the clothing manufacturer, to design a line of sunglasses bearing the Levi's name. Terms were not disclosed.

headline: Artillery Duels Spread in Lebanon, Killing 15
abstract: LEAD: At least 15 people were reported killed and about 40 wounded today as fierce artillery battles raged in much of Lebanon.

headline: Arizona Bank Expects a Loss
abstract: LEAD: The Valley National Corporation said today that it would add $181 million to its reserves for loan losses and that it expected a $90 million loss in the second quarter as a result.

headline: Iraqi Gulf Ports May Reopen
abstract: LEAD: Iraq is expected to resume crude oil exports from the Persian Gulf in June, the Middle East Economic Survey reported today.

headline: India's Envoy to Sri Lanka Gets a Hotter Seat: Pakistan
abstract: LEAD: India's Ambassador in Sri Lanka for the last four turbulent years, in which more than 50,000 Indian troops entered the country to put down an ethnic rebellion, has been named envoy to Pakistan.

headline: Chrysler Missouri Plant
abstract: LEAD: The Chrysler Corporation said today that it was nearing completion of a $124 million modernization of a plant at Fenton, Mo., outside St. Louis, where it will produce new versions of the Dodge Daytona and Chrysler Lebaron.

headline: Warsaw Journal; In an Unpredictable Land, the Pariah as Candidate
abstract: LEAD: The indictment in Jacek Kuron's trial for anti-Government activity in 1983 describes him this way: ''Not working, no estate, no decorations, nonassociated.'' Despite such meager qualifications, Mr. Kuron has been a favorite target of official repression over the years.

headline: NWA Rejects Offer by Davis
abstract: LEAD: NWA Inc., parent company of Northwest Airlines, today rejected a $2.62 billion takeover offer by the billionaire oilman Marvin Davis, saying it was too low.

headline: Even Wall Street Is Paved With Rust
abstract: LEAD: America's $700 billion financial services industry is fast becoming our nation's next ''rust belt'' as Japanese banks, securities firms and insurance companies invest heavily to overtake yet another complacent American industry.

headline: Consolidated Gas Sells Debentures
abstract: LEAD: The Consolidated Natural Gas Company yesterday sold $100 million of 10-year debentures through competitive bidding.

headline: U.S. Charges Greek Bank Ran Scheme to Evade Tax
abstract: LEAD: The Government yesterday accused a large Greek bank and 14 employees of running an extensive money-laundering scheme that allowed customers to send at least $700 million to Greece to evade American taxes.

headline: Quake in Remote China Area
abstract: LEAD: A strong earthquake rocked a remote region of China near the Burmese border early today, toppling homes and cracking streets, the official New China News Agency said. The quake, measuring 6.3 on the open-ended Richter Scale, was centered in Hepai and Sipaishan in the southwestern province of Yunnan.

headline: After a Decade of Thatcher Are Her Ideals Now Britain's?
abstract: LEAD: Ten years ago, Britain was the sick man of Europe, its industries crumbling, its economy paralyzed by intractable labor disputes, its political and intellectual leaders resigned to genteel but inevitable decline.

headline: Business Digest
abstract: LEAD:  The Media Business  WPP Group has begun an assault on another U.S. ad agency, making an unsolicited $730 million offer to buy the Ogilvy Group. If the bid succeeds, it will create the world's second-largest advertising company, after Saatchi & Saatchi, which like WPP is based in London. A merger would join some of the best-known names in advertising and continue the wave of mergers that has transformed the ad and marketing-communications industries.

headline: Administration Lobbies for its Savings Plan
abstract: LEAD: The Bush Administration moved today to prevent the House Ways and Means Committee from approving a plan that would put the Government's entire cost of the savings and loan rescue on the books.

headline: Jordan's Revolt Is Against Austerity
abstract: LEAD: The young men hauled tires and debris across a street and set the barricade alight so that black smoke curled up under a bright sun. A jeep full of soldiers pulled to a halt, and the men poured from it with their automatic rifles, scanning the roofs of the square, bleached-stone homes for rock throwers.

headline: Carlyle Won't Raise Bid for Fairchild
abstract: LEAD: The Carlyle Group said it does not intend to raise its final bid of $17.50 a share for Fairchild Industries, which agreed on Monday to merge with Banner Industries, another aerospace company.

headline: Chrysler Net Up 90.8%, Helped by Charge in '88
abstract: LEAD: The Chrysler Corporation yesterday reported a 90.8 percent increase in its first-quarter net income, helped by a special charge in the first quarter of last year.

headline: Bonds Appear Poised for Advance
abstract: LEAD: The fixed-income securities market appears poised for another advance this week, as the prospects for a slower economy grow and fears of further weakness in the dollar wane, analysts say.

headline: Delaware Courts Get Tough Toward Investment Bankers
abstract: LEAD: Investment bankers are being sharply criticized in the Delaware courts, the nation's most important forum for takeover battles, for playing favorites when they oversee auctions of companies and for giving arbitrary investment opinions about the value of bids.

headline: HONG KONG SHUNS VIETNAM REFUGEES
abstract: LEAD: The Hong Kong Government today sent 400 Vietnamese men, women and children to a remote, nearly uninhabited island where they will live at first on cold rations without even rudimentary shelter.

headline: WPP Tells Ogilvy It Will Raise Offer
abstract: LEAD: The bitter battle between two of the world's leading marketing communications companies intensified during the weekend when the WPP Group P.L.C., the British parent of the J. Walter Thompson advertising agency, told the Ogilvy Group Inc. that it would raise its bid for the company.

headline: 'Brown Tide' Leaves Long Island Waters But Puzzle Remains
abstract: LEAD: The huge algae masses that muddied waters and devastated the rich marine ecosystem of eastern Long Island have subsided as mysteriously as they first appeared four years ago.

headline: Europeans Adopt New Sanctions Against Chinese
abstract: LEAD: Stepping up their pressure on China to stop executions and repression of political dissidents, European Community leaders announced a series of new reprisals today against Beijing, including a suspension of military cooperation and arms sales.

headline: Hurt by Excess Inventory, Ashton-Tate Expects Loss
abstract: LEAD: Facing large excess inventories of its data base management programs among United States software distributors, the Ashton-Tate Corporation said today that it expected to report a loss for the second quarter on reduced revenues.

headline: Dow Offsets Loss With a 6.60-Point Gain
abstract: LEAD: Stocks moved moderately higher yesterday as the Dow Jones industrial average rose 6.60 points to close at 2,304.80. That offset, exactly, its loss on Tuesday.

headline: Savings Bill Battle Is Seen
abstract: LEAD: Republicans in the House of Representatives will again mount a fight on Wednesday for an amendment to President Bush's bailout plan that would weaken the tough capital standards for the savings and loan industry that were approved earlier this month by the House Banking Committee.

headline: Detained Yugoslav a Suicide
abstract: LEAD: An ethnic Albanian committed suicide by jumping out a window during interrogation as security forces investigated sabotage in Kosovo, newspapers said today. The Belgrade daily Vecernje Novosti said the ethnic Albanian, Djemaili Rasit Berisa, leaped to his death Thursday while being questioned in Prizren, a Kosovo town.

headline: Dissident Chinese Gather in the West
abstract: LEAD: It was 70 years ago that a movement of Chinese students and intellectuals, shocked by their Government's weakness in the face of Japanese aggression, engaged in a period of soul searching and re-evaluation known as the May Fourth Movement. A result was the formation of the Communist Party that now rules

headline: Company News; Kubota Will Buy 15% Stake in Rasna
abstract: LEAD: Kubota Ltd., a Tokyo-based manufacturer, said it would invest $10 million to acquire a 15 percent equity share in the Rasna Corporation, a new company based in San Jose, Calif., that produces mechanical design and analysis software. Kubota will also establish a 50-50 joint venture with Rasna to market its software products in

headline: Sandinista Opponent Goes Home After 7-Year Exile
abstract: LEAD: After seven years in exile, a leading member of the anti-Sandinista rebel directorate returned here today to an enthusiastic opposition welcome to take an active role in national elections scheduled for February 1990.

headline: Murdoch and Maxwell Link TV From Cable and Satellite
abstract: LEAD: In a deal showing that even old rivalries can fall to new technology, the media entrepreneurs Robert Maxwell and Rupert Murdoch joined forces today in a multimillion-dollar agreement linking satellite and cable television.

headline: Leftist Plans Rebirth of Sao Paulo's Schools
abstract: LEAD: Twenty-five years ago, Paulo Freire's world as a radical educator crashed around him.

headline: People
abstract: LEAD: * Dominick F. Rossi Jr., an executive vice president of N. W. Ayer, was promoted to director of national operations.

headline: Money Manager Cuts Robins Stake
abstract: LEAD: Michael H. Steinhardt, a New York money manager, has lowered his stake in the A. H. Robins Company to 2.74 percent from 5.6 percent. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Mr. Steinhardt said he had sold the shares between June 1 and Tuesday at prices ranging from $26.50 to $30.50 a share.

headline: Business and Health; Controlling Costs: One Good Sign
abstract: LEAD: THE early numbers on Allied-Signal Inc.'s daring attempt to control health care costs look so good that the company is wary. They may be too good to be true. The many employers beginning similar arrangements hope not.

headline: CHANGE IS URGENT, GORBACHEV INSISTS
abstract: LEAD: Mikhail S. Gorbachev told Communist Party leaders this week that the elections last month were a mandate for more radical change from a public embittered by the country's economic crisis, nationalist unrest, crime and mismanagement.

headline: Loyal Haitian Troops Seize Garrison Held by Rebel Unit
abstract: LEAD: After more than 20 hours of often-ferocious shooting that turned the heart of the Haitian capital into a combat zone, loyalist troops this afternoon captured the garrison of a rebel army unit that had been trying to overthrow the Government for nearly a week.

headline: Warning On Trade 'Bashing'
abstract: LEAD: President Bush's chief economist, Michael J. Boskin, warned today that ''bashing'' trade partners like Japan could lead to a trade war and a recession.

headline: G.M. Braking Plan Reported
abstract: LEAD: The General Motors Corporation intends to make anti-lock braking systems standard equipment in many of its large cars by the 1991 model year and in about half of all its cars by 1995, a trade publication reported today.

headline: China Called Top Copyright Pirate
abstract: LEAD: Companies producing books, records, films, computer software and other so-called intellectual property contended today that 12 countries, headed by China, are depriving the United States of more than $1.3 billion a year of foreign earnings through piracy of copyrighted material.

headline: Hundreds of Lebanese Flee to Cyprus by Ferry
abstract: LEAD: A ferry carrying hundreds of Lebanese fleeing the nation's strife sailed today for Cyprus as shells rained down on the port of Junieh.

headline: Excerpts From Speeches at Moscow Party Meeting: Raging at the Changes
abstract: LEAD: Following are excerpts from speeches to the Soviet Communist Party Central Committee meeting on Tuesday, published today by Pravda and translated by The New York Times:  Yuri F. Solovyev  First Secretary of Leningrad region, candidate member of the Politburo

headline: Ford's Quarterly Profit Up 1.2%; Decline Expected for '89
abstract: LEAD: The Ford Motor Company managed to post a slim increase today in first-quarter earnings, despite lower United States automotive profits and a $100 million drop in earnings from its finance subsidiary.

headline: Beretta U.S.A. Contract
abstract: LEAD: The Army said on Monday that Beretta U.S.A., a subsidiary of the Italian arms maker Fabbrica d'Armi Pietro Beretta S.p.A., would continue suppling 9-millimeter handguns to the military. Although the Beretta unit beat out seven competitiors in 1985 to replace the Army's old Colt .45 pistols, Congress in 1987 ordered a new competition to make sure American companies received a fair judgment.

headline: Dollar High Against Yen And Mark
abstract: LEAD: The dollar rose sharply yesterday, again surpassing 2 West German marks and topping 146 yen, its highest level since October 1987.

headline: Allis-Chalmers Names A Nederlander as Head
abstract: LEAD: Robert E. Nederlander, a member of the theater-owning family in New York, is going far off Broadway in his latest business venture. Mr. Nederlander has been named the chairman and chief executive of the Allis-Chalmers Corporation in Milwaukee.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Domecq Importers Inc., a wine and spirits importer, to Tromson Monroe Advertising, with a budget of $3 million.

headline: The Built-In Bias Against HDTV
abstract: LEAD: For those alarmed about America's supposed loss of competitiveness, digital audio tape - a technology that makes nearly distortion-free home recording possible - is the latest example of how the United States has lost its lead. But history shows that new technology often displaces existing technology slowly and with difficulty.

headline: Mexico Will Seek Debt Relief
abstract: LEAD: Seeking ways to lighten its debt burden, Mexico will ask its American creditors and other foreign bankers to cut the value of their loans by $20 billion to $30 billion, international banking officials said today.

headline: Ito Bows Out as Takeshita Successor

headline: Report on Harrods
abstract: LEAD: The British Government rejected demands for immediate publication of a secret report into the takeover of Harrods department store by three Egyptian brothers after a bid by Lonrho P.L.C. was blocked by the Government. Lord Young, the Trade and Industry Minister, said premature publication would bar prosecutions for wrongdoing by the Serious Fraud Office.

headline: Strike Grounds Qantas
abstract: LEAD: The Australian airline Qantas canceled all flights today because of an engineers' strike. The international carrier said in a statement that it was trying to transfer the 10,000 passengers affected to other airlines but that it would not be possible to accommodate all of them. Five hundred engineers who check maintenance work on planes and certify them for flying began the stoppage on Monday in a pay dispute.

headline: Investors Sue Penny Broker
abstract: LEAD: A group of New England investors has filed a class-action lawsuit seeking hundreds of thousands of dollars from Blinder, Robinson & Company, a Denver penny-stock brokerage.

headline: Lithuania Declares A Moscow Tax Law To Be Non-Binding
abstract: LEAD: Lithuania has became the first Soviet republic to defy Moscow's taxing authority, announcing today in official newspapers that Lithuanians will not be obliged to pay a new nationwide highway tax.

headline: Seabrook Owners File a New Plan
abstract: LEAD: The owners of the Seabrook nuclear power plant have filed papers with the Nuclear Regulatory Commission that they believe clears remaining obstacles to receiving a low-power license. Seabrook, in New Hampshire near Massachusetts, has been blocked from operating by a dispute over emergency planning.

headline: Prices Decline in Light Trading
abstract: LEAD: Treasury note and bond prices slipped in light trading yesterday, despite the release of economic reports that were in line with expectations in the credit markets.

headline: MEXICO LOOSENING INVESTMENT RULES
abstract: LEAD: Continuing its efforts to make the country's economy more competitive worldwide, the Mexican Government today announced a sweeping liberalization of its foreign investment regulations. It revoked measures that have prevented majority foreign ownership of businesses and opened to foreign investment some areas that have previously been off limits altogether.

abstract: LEAD: Seeking to become an issuer like the United States Treasury, the World Bank said yesterday that in coming months it plans to offer $1.5 billion worth of new debt that will be simultaneously underwritten and distributed abroad and in the United States.

headline: Peanut Use Rises in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: United States peanut consumption rose by 10.8 percent in the first eight months of the current peanut marketing year from the period a year earlier, according to a Department of Agriculture report. It said that Americans ate 18 percent more peanut butter, 7.2 percent more salted nuts and 1.2 percent more candy bars containing nuts in the period.

headline: Agreement on Sale By Hospital Corp.
abstract: LEAD: The Hospital Corporation of America has agreed to sell 10 hospitals and seven nursing homes in Britain to BUPA Health Services Ltd. for $142 million. The concerns have reached an agreement in principle, but have no definitive accord, the Nashville-based Hospital Corporation said. The sale is to be completed within 45 days.

headline: A U.N. OFFICE LOOKS TO PREVENT WARS
abstract: LEAD: Officials here have decided that it is not enough for the United Nations to send peacekeepers to troubled areas; it must recognize conflicts before they erupt and try to defuse them.

headline: Yugoslav Inflation Rises
abstract: LEAD: Yugoslavia's Bureau of Statistics reported today that prices soared by a monthly record of 92.6 percentage points, to a rate of 490.1 percent, compared with 397.5 percent in March. In April 1988, inflation was 152 percent. Yugoslav economists said inflation could rise to almost 1,000 percent by the end of the year, further depressing living standards that have already plummeted to their lowest levels since the late 1960's.

abstract: LEAD: The Burger King Corporation pulled almost half of its $150 million advertising account from N. W. Ayer yesterday, after a tumultuous year and a half in which its ads and marketing strategy came under harsh industry criticism as being erratic and ineffective.

headline: Atalanta-Sosnoff Buys Airline Stake
abstract: LEAD: An investment group led by the Atalanta-Sosnoff Capital Corporation, a New York money management concern controlled by Martin T. Sosnoff, has bought the equivalent of an 8.46 percent stake in America West Airlines Inc. for $17.7 million. In a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Mr. Sosnoff said the America West shares were for investment purposes only.

headline: Dow in China Deal
abstract: LEAD: The Dow Chemical Company entered a joint venture with China's Zhejiang Chemical Factory to build a $50 million chemical plant in Ningbo, China. The new company, the Zhejiang Pacific Chemical Corporation, in Zhejiang Province on the East China Sea, will produce 20,000 metric tons a year of polyether polyol, Dow said.

abstract: LEAD: The rabbits are plump and destined for the pot, and so, too, are the pigeons. Mohammed Awad, who keeps them in his yard, says that in their small way they represent a weapon against occupation.

abstract: LEAD: As turmoil swept through West German politics and the North Atlantic alliance, one man seemed to stand serenely and triumphantly content. For Hans-Dietrich Genscher, this was a moment to savor.

headline: Plans for Varity
abstract: LEAD: The Varity Corporation is considering a stock buyback, reverse share splits and restoring its common stock dividend as ways to raise its share price, the company's chairman and chief executive officer, Victor Rice, said. Varity, which makes farm and industrial machinery, is also looking at the possibility of moving its headquarters to the United States.

abstract: LEAD: A veteran centrist politician was effectively proclaimed the Chilean opposition's presidential candidate today after winning the backing of moderate leftist parties.

abstract: LEAD: The Supreme Court refused to narrow the scope of the Federal racketeering law, which has become a weapon in private lawsuits. Page D1.

headline: Lonrho Loses Final Round On Harrods

headline: Disney Stock Soars
abstract: LEAD: The stock of the Walt Disney Company gained sharply today for the second consecutive day, propelled by strong attendance at its new movie theme park and overall enthusiasm for the company's prospects, analysts said. Disney rose $5 a share today, to $92.125, after climbing $1.25 on Thursday. The movie park, which opened on May 1 as part of the Disney World complex in Orlando, Fla., is expected to increase total attendance at Disney's Orlando site by about 20 percent, said Christopher Dixon, an analyst for Kidder, Peabody.

abstract: LEAD: Bruised by major expenses from its recent takeover by the investment firm Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Company and the costly failure of its ''smokeless'' cigarette, RJR Nabisco Inc. yesterday reported a 62 percent drop in first-quarter earnings.

abstract: LEAD: Thousands of Muslims occupied Parliament Square this afternoon to demand that the novel ''The Satanic Verses'' be banned.

abstract: LEAD: Louis Weinberg, a professor of electrical engineering and mathematics at City College, had been planning for some time for the International Conference on Circuits and Systems that had been scheduled for Nanjing on July 6 and 7.

abstract: LEAD: Seymour R. Cray, the legendary developer of supercomputers, predicted here today that the new company he was leaving Cray Research Inc. to form could eventually grow into a billion-dollar operation. But Wall Street reacted negatively to the news of the the splitting of Cray Research, sending its stock down $6, or 10.8 percent, to $49.75, in heavy selling.

headline: Hong Kong Inflation
abstract: LEAD: Hong Kong's broadest index of inflation rose 9.5 percent in March from a year earlier, the Government said today. During the first quarter of 1989, the seasonally adjusted consumer price index increased at an average rate of nine-tenths of a percent a month. The Government said it still expected overall inflation of 8.5 percent in 1989.

headline: China's Imports Jump
abstract: LEAD: The Chinese Government said last week that exports had risen slightly in May while imports soared, a situation that reflects the country's economic and political turmoil. Customs officials said China exported $4.43 billion of goods in May, up eight-tenths of a percent from May 1988. Imports were up 21.1 percent, to $5.31 billion, in the period, the official New China News Agency reported.

abstract: LEAD: France said today it was expelling three South African Embassy officials to protest what it described as an illegal effort by Pretoria to acquire a stolen British Blowpipe missile in Paris. Officials said one of those being expelled was Daniel Storm, who was found in a Paris hotel on April 21 with three Protestant extremists from Northern Ireland.

abstract: LEAD: President Bush met today with President Hosni Mubarak and later said the United States and Egypt agreed that Israel should end its occupation of Arab lands. They also agreed that an international conference could help bring about peace in the Middle East if properly arranged.

headline: Angolans Reported Escaping Into Namibia
abstract: LEAD: Hundreds of Angolans are fleeing into neighboring Namibia to escape fighting between right-wing Angolan rebels and Government troops, a Namibian spokesman said today.

headline: Sakharov in Appeal on China
abstract: LEAD: Andrei D. Sakharov, the Soviet human rights campaigner, urged world leaders today to press China to cancel death sentences imposed on pro-democracy demonstrators. Dr. Sakharov, on his second trip abroad since being freed from internal exile in 1986, sent telegrams to Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the Soviet President, and Western leaders.

abstract: LEAD: In the brief televised image broadcast as he was elevated to the leadership of the Communist Party in China, Jiang Zemin looked a bit glum, his brow slightly furrowed. He may have been reflecting on a disquieting realization: the job he is assuming is a precarious one.

headline: Rate Rise By Japanese Is Expected
abstract: LEAD: Japan is expected to raise its discount rate on Tuesday for the first time in nine years, ending an era of loose money policy here that fueled Japan's economic boom through this decade.

headline: Soviets Report an Armed Rampage in Kazakhstan
abstract: LEAD: Apparently distressed by economic hardships in their region, armed youths have gone on a deadly rampage in the Central Asian republic of Kazakhstan in the latest eruption of violence in the southern Soviet republics, Tass reported today.

headline: Koor Industries
abstract: LEAD: Koor Industries, Israel's largest industrial conglomerate, reached agreement today with foreign and domestic creditors on repaying its huge debts. headline: 2 Big Futures Exchanges in a Race
abstract: LEAD: With the global market for the futures business as the prize, the nation's two biggest commodity exchanges are battling to develop the pre-eminent system for round-the-clock electronic trading. Such a system, by allowing traders to buy and sell futures contracts at computer terminals, could eventually replace the physical trading floors.

headline: Ex-Pullman Head Returns, With an Interest in Buyouts
abstract: LEAD: Thomas M. Begel, who built up the Pullman Company through acquisitions before selling it last fall, is back in business with a new investment company and an appetite for medium-sized industrial companies.

headline: Scott Selling Land To Crown Pacific
abstract: LEAD: The Scott Paper Company announced it would sell 194,000 acres of timberlands in western Washington to Crown Pacific Ltd. for about $230 million. Scott announced plans to sell its timberlands in the Northwest in 1983, and the agreement with Crown represents all but about 16,000 acres.

headline: Rig Count Rises Again
abstract: LEAD: The number of rigs exploring for oil continued an upward climb last week, increasing by 15, to a total of 810, Baker Hughes Inc. reported today. It was the fifth straight weekly gain in the nationwide count. A year ago, the count stood at 894.

headline: Mexico Arrests Investigator In Political Journalist's Murder
abstract: LEAD: Mexico's most politically charged murder case, the 1984 shooting of the country's best-known journalist, appears to have been cracked with the arrest of a former security official who headed the initial investigation.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Hollywood Spent More For TV Ads Last Year
abstract: LEAD: Movie advertising on television reflected the glowing performance of the film industry last year, jumping 17 percent above the level a year earlier, according to a survey. Hollywood spent $383 million promoting new film releases in 1988, according to the Television Bureau of Advertising, which compiled the survey.

headline: Italian Socialists Pass Communists at Polls
abstract: LEAD: Italy's Socialist Party has outpolled the Communists for the first time in 40 years in local elections that will influence the formation of a new national government.

headline: Film Festival Leader
abstract: LEAD: Marcio Moreira, the vice chairman of McCann-Erickson, was chosen Wednesday to be president of the 20-member jury at this week's International Advertising Film Festival in Cannes, France. Mr. Moreira is the third American selected for that post since 1985. Jerry Della Femina, chairman of Della Femina McNamee WCRS, headed the jury in 1987, and Keith Reinhard, chairman of DDB Needham, was president in 1985.

headline: TWO FOUND GUILTY ON FRAUD CHARGES IN PENTAGON TRIAL
abstract: LEAD: A Federal jury today convicted two executives of a California military contractor of conspiracy and wire fraud.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD:  Debt

headline: Burger King to Cut 550 Jobs in Revamping
abstract: LEAD: The Burger King Corporation said today that it would lay off about 550 of its 1,500 non-restaurant employees in a restructuring after its acquisition earlier this year by Grand Metropolitan P.L.C. of Britain.

headline: The U.N. Today
abstract: LEAD:  General Assembly  PREPARATORY COMMITTEE FOR SPECIAL SESSION ON ECONOMIC ISSUES - 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.  WORKING GROUP ON THE DRAFTING OF AN INTERNATIONAL CONVENTION ON THE PROTECTION OF MIGRANT WORKERS - 10:30 A.M. and 3 P.M.

headline: France Stands by Nuclear Power
abstract: LEAD: The accidents at Three Mile Island and Chernobyl have set back the nuclear industry in many nations, but not in France, where reactors supply 70 percent of the electricity, the highest proportion in the world. The United States figure is 18 percent.

headline: Panama Transition Called Impossible Now
abstract: LEAD: The Organization of American States has given a team of mediators six weeks to work out a democratic transition in Panama, but a top Panamanian official said no solution was possible as long as his country was ''permanently threatened'' by the United States.

headline: China's Date With Destiny
abstract: LEAD: Perhaps the most surprising thing about this week's illegal student demonstrations is that the Government permitted them at all: that the nation's authoritarian leaders have allowed their sleep to be interrupted for the last two nights by thousands of students trying to force their way into the Communist Party headquarters and bellowing such slogans as ''Overthrow the dictatorship!

headline: Nuclear Battery Converts Reactor Waste Products
abstract: LEAD: Paul Brown, a college dropout who is vice president of Peripheral Systems Inc., a six-year-old technology concern in Portland, Ore., has won patent approval for a nuclear battery.

headline: Hunger Strike in South Africa
abstract: LEAD: Seventeen black political detainees have begun a new hunger strike in Diepkloof Prison in Johannesburg, vowing not to eat or drink until they are freed, human rights activists said today. A spokesman for the Department of Law and Order restated the Government policy of moving hunger strikers to a prison near Bloemfontein, a city far from centers of unrest like Johannesburg, Cape Town and Durban.

headline: Businessland's Life Without Compaq
abstract: LEAD: In Businessland Inc.'s early days, Stewart Alsop, a knowledgeable observer of the computer industry, used to say derisively that the company was ''masquerading'' as a personal computer retailer. By this he meant that its numerous storefronts across the country were merely a facade, and that the real engine behind sales was its huge sales force that called directly on corporate customers.

headline: Nicaraguan Opposition Forging Election Demands
abstract: LEAD: Working under a deadline established by a regional peace accord, Nicaragua's opposition parties have begun intense negotiations on electoral demands that they say will form their minimum requirements for a fair vote in national elections scheduled for February 1990.

headline: Maxwell Gets Israeli Stake
abstract: LEAD: The British publisher Robert Maxwell has paid $30.4 million for a stake in Israel's largest drug manufacturing company, a spokeswoman for the company said today. It was Mr. Maxwell's third Israeli investment in 10 months.

headline: Perkin-Elmer Plans to Shed Unit
abstract: LEAD: The Perkin-Elmer Corporation, which pioneered development of a significant machine for making advanced semiconductor chips during the early 1970's, said yesterday that it would withdraw from the business, blaming Japanese competition.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Aircoa Hotel Partners L.P., Denver, announced the execution of a purchase and sale agreement by Kona Operating Partnership L.P. for the sale of its Kona Village Resort in Hawaii. The price is $55 million.

headline: Hanson Coup: Smith Corona Offer
abstract: LEAD: When Hanson P.L.C. bought the SCM Corporation for $930 million in 1986, many analysts and executives thought the acquisitive British industrial conglomerate had overpaid. But every few months since then, it seems, Hanson has announced a stunning new deal for SCM assets to show the skeptics how wrong they were.

headline: Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, 89, Relentless Founder of Iran's Islamic Republic
abstract: LEAD: The life of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini was so shadowy, with such an overlay of myth and rumor, that there was lingering disagreement or uncertainty about his ancestry, his true name and his date of birth.

headline: Bundesbank Move on Rates Causes Sharp Drop in Dollar
abstract: LEAD: The dollar dropped sharply yesterday on a surprise move by the Bundesbank of West Germany to raise its two primary interest rates by half a percentage point.

headline: The D-RAM Consortium
abstract: LEAD: On Wednesday, seven semiconductor and computer companies announced that they will finance the creation of a company to mass produce memory chips - the most commonly used chips. The company, U.S. Memories Inc., will make dynamic random access memory chips, or D-RAM's, using technology from International Business Machines, which only makes the chips for its own use.

headline: Strong Dollar May Cut Prices But It Lowers Profits as Well
abstract: LEAD: From giant corporate headquarters to small businesses to Americans traveling abroad, the startling rise of the dollar over the last six weeks is beginning to be felt.

headline: Warsaw Journal; For Paper, Jungle (and Censor) Await
abstract: LEAD: This month, the most influential source of uncensored information in Poland was laid to rest. Next month it will be reborn as the first independently published daily newspaper in the East bloc.

headline: Reporter's Notebook; Spies Learn Students Can Be Stern Teachers
abstract: LEAD: A young secret policeman, or perhaps he was just an innocent student, held a banner the wrong way during today's demonstration.

headline: China Exchange: From Gossip to Trash Bags
abstract: LEAD: The message went up on the international computer network that links thousands of corporations, universities and research centers around the world: the students demonstrating in Tiananmen Square in Beijing needed garbage bags.

headline: This Time, Many Candidates for Soviet Voters
abstract: LEAD: Soviet voters, who rebelled six weeks ago at the attempt of Communist Party figures to arrange unopposed election victories for themselves, returned to ballot booths today to find feast where there had been famine.

abstract: LEAD:               Previous   Year     In percent   Yesterday   Day   Ago              PRIME RATE   11.50   11.50   8.50        DISCOUNT RATE   7.00   7.00   6.00        FEDERAL FUNDS   9.78   9.82   7.09        3-MO.
