headline: Ethiopia Coup Attempt Reported; Authorities Say Revolt Is Crushed
abstract: LEAD: Senior military officers staged a coup attempt in Ethiopia Tuesday, hours after President Mengistu Haile Mariam left on a visit to East Germany.

headline: Minorco's Gold Fields Bid Stalled
abstract: LEAD: A $4.2 billion hostile takeover bid by Minorco S.A., the world's largest gold-mining company, for Consolidated Gold Fields P.L.C., the second largest, seemed in serious jeopardy yesterday.

headline: Thermo May Bid For Milton Roy
abstract: LEAD: The Thermo Electron Corporation said it had acquired a 5.9 percent stake in the Milton Roy Company and was interested in acquiring the St. Petersburg, Fla., concern. Milton Roy's stock jumped $1.125 today, to $17.625 a share, on the New York Stock Exchange. With 5.6 million shares outstanding, Milton

headline: Medical Unit Holds Talks
abstract: LEAD: A group including members of the Bass family said that delegates had met with certain directors of American Medical International Inc. to discuss ways to enhance shareholder value.

headline: Bush Picks Envoy to Pretoria To Lead the Foreign Service
abstract: LEAD: President Bush said Thursday that he would nominate Edward J. Perkins, a career diplomat and most recently the Ambassador to South Africa, as director general of the Foreign Service.

headline: Dividend Meetings
abstract: LEAD: Following is a parial list of dividend meetings for the week of April 24, 1989:  MONDAY  Airborne Fght Corp  Armstrong World Inds Inc  Boeing Co  Cinc Milacron Inc  Consol Freightways Inc  Foster Wheeler Corp  Golden West Finl Corp  Kennametal Inc  Lubrizol Corp  Mercury Sav & Ln Inc  Republic Gypsum Co

headline: Bankers Cool to Appeal By Brady on Debt Plan
abstract: LEAD: Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady appealed today to leading commercial bankers to embrace the principles of his plan for reducing the debt burden of less developed countries.

headline: U.S. and Europe in Accord On Industrial Standards
abstract: LEAD: The United States and the European Community announced an agreement today intended to make it easier for American companies to comment as European companies set new standards on industrial products.

headline: Europe Limit On U.S. TV
abstract: LEAD: The European Parliament adopted proposals today for a law that would limit the number of United States television programs shown in Europe, despite intense lobbying from the United States.

headline: Book-Contract Gambles That Rarely Pay
abstract: LEAD: WITH so many recent six- and seven-figure book contracts, one could easily conclude that publishers have gone overboard in embracing Samuel Johnson's dictum that ''No man but a blockhead ever wrote except for money.''

headline: Profit Scoreboard
abstract: LEAD:            Net Income   Percent       Jan.-Mar.   Change       1989   From '88       Amdahl Corp.   $ 45,600,000    +7.0        Bethlehem Steel Corp.   64,700,000    -24.2        Chevron Corp.   313,000,000    -52.1        Cyprus Minerals Co.   81,000,000    +204.5        Dow Corning Corp.   41,100,000    +9.3        Engelhard Corp.   14,400,000    +7.5        Greyhound Corp.

headline: Income Realty
abstract: LEAD: Two pension funds have formed a corporation to make an offer for the shares of the Income Opportunity Realty Trust that they do not own. The offer, which a spokesman said was believed to be the first by a pension fund, is at $7.50 a share. Income Opportunity, based in Emeryville, Calif., has about 3.7 million shares outstanding, giving the company a total value of about $27.7 million.

headline: KOREA ADDRESSES ABUSES OF ITS PAST
abstract: LEAD: In an unusual attempt at compromise, Government and opposition party leaders are struggling to agree on the issues of whom to punish and whom to compensate for the excesses of South Korea's authoritarian past and how to insure that the old abuses never recur.

headline: Treasury Notes and Bonds Rise
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds rose moderately yesterday after being buffeted by rumors that provoked wild moves in the dollar, which lately has been the main influence on the fixed-income securities market.

headline: Sabre System Cuts Its Price
abstract: LEAD: After three months of trying to sell shares in Sabre, their joint reservations system, American Airlines and Delta Air Lines said on Tuesday that they were cutting the price by 25 percent on the first segment of the partnership to help speed Government approval.

headline: 57 REPORTED DEAD IN UZBEK VIOLENCE
abstract: LEAD: At least 57 people were killed over the weekend in clashes in the Soviet republic of Uzbekistan, Soviet officials said today.

headline: I.B.M. Gain Eases Fear Of a Slump
abstract: LEAD: Allaying some investors' fears that a computer industry downturn was imminent, the International Business Machines Corporation reported yesterday that its first-quarter revenues rose 5.6 percent, to $12.7 billion, a result that was slightly better than analysts had expected.

headline: Turmoil in China; Eager Not to Offend, Soviet Congress Criticizes Outside Pressure on China
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Congress of People's Deputies today condemned outside efforts to bring pressure on China, saying that the upheavals in that country were purely an internal matter.

headline: BEIJING RESIDENTS BLOCK ARMY MOVE NEAR CITY CENTER
abstract: LEAD: Tens of thousands of Beijing students and workers surged onto the streets early this morning to turn back more than 2,000 troops who were marching toward Tiananmen Square.

headline: New-Home Sales Up By 10.9%
abstract: LEAD: Sales of new homes were up a strong 10.9 percent in April, the Government said today, but housing economists said the industry would remain sluggish at least into summer because of high interest rates.

headline: Helen Suzman, Liberal Voice, Will Leave the Pretoria Fray
abstract: LEAD: Helen Suzman, South Africa's most celebrated white anti-apartheid campaigner, has announced her retirement from Parliament, where hers was for many years the sole liberal voice raised against racial discrimination.

headline: U.S. Warns Moscow on High-Technology Thefts
abstract: LEAD: Four days after President Bush signaled a relaxation of of trade restrictions with the Soviet Union, Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher called on Moscow today to stop stealing high-technology secrets and to end harassment of Soviet visitors to the American Embassy in Moscow.

headline: Opposition in Panama Urges Wide Strike to Rout Noriega
abstract: LEAD: Struggling to devise new tactics in the face of increasing Government repression, the opposition to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega called today for a general strike starting on Wednesday.

headline: Excerpts From Speech By Bush on Polish Aid
abstract: LEAD: Following are excerpts from President Bush's address today in Hamtramck, Mich., as recorded by The New York Times through the facilities of Cable News Network.

headline: Lyons Journal; For a Staid City, Neo-Gaullism With Gallic Verve
abstract: LEAD: The mayors of France's staid second city are supposed to die in office. Until late March, Lyons was so politically stable that it had only had four mayors in this century, and one of them, Edouard Herriot, reigned for 54 years.

headline: Productivity Is More (or Less) Than a Hard Day's Work
abstract: LEAD: ''Productivity's Little Secret: Hard Work,'' a Business Forum article appearing on May 14 by Dan Subotnik, prompted an unusually large response from readers. Some of their comments follow.  To the Editor:

headline: Communist Emerges as Key Player in Greek Crisis
abstract: LEAD: In the 18 years during which the Communist guerrilla fighter was jailed, then banished to an island and condemned to death, he probably could not have predicted the phone calls from the presidential palace and from politicians of all stripes coming his way this week.

headline: Iran Cites Oil Windfall
abstract: LEAD: Higher crude oil prices have brought a $1.5 billion windfall to Iran's oil revenue in the last three months, the country's oil minister, Gholam Reza Aghazadeh, said today. ''We are now selling our oil at 50 cents to a dollar more than official OPEC prices,'' Mr. Aghazadeh told the Teheran radio.

headline: Your Money; For Some Bonds, It's Time to Sell
abstract: LEAD: Investors who bought long-term municipal bonds or unit investment trusts made up of such bonds in the high-interest-rate climate of the early to mid-1980's invested wisely. As rates have generally dropped in recent years, the prices of those securities have risen, and credit market experts say investors should now consider whether to sell those holdings.

headline: Eastern in Accord To Sell 3 Jetliners
abstract: LEAD: Eastern Airlines said it had agreed to sell three 727 jetliners by the Boeing Company for $9 million to the Express One Corporation, a Dallas-based aircraft company. The sale, which must be approved by a Federal Bankruptcy Court in New York, is part of the plan by Eastern to shrink to about two-thirds its former size by selling $1.8 billion in assets.

headline: Nestle Reversal On Offering
abstract: LEAD: The Swiss food giant Nestle S.A., in a turnabout from a position it took last week, said today that a planned securities offering to raise nearly 800 million Swiss francs, or about $460 million, would go ahead despite initial objections from a group of stockholders.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Y.&R. Ventures
abstract: LEAD: James W. Hood will become the president and chief executive of Young & Rubicam Ventures, a new marketing consulting and investment banking subsidiary. The company was formed by the advertising agency after it and Paine Webber parted ways over their two-year-old joint venture to perform the same services.

headline: California Offers $200 Million Issue
abstract: LEAD: California is offering $200 million of general obligation bonds through underwriters led by the Bank of America's Bank Investment Securities division.

headline: Company News; G.M. Plans Some Summer Closings
abstract: LEAD: The General Motors Corporation said it planned to shut down some of its assembly plants for a month or longer this summer to help reduce inventories and provide time for plant retooling as part of its previously announced plan to reduce production in the third quarter of the year.

headline: Triborough Bridge Authority Bonds
abstract: LEAD: The Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority is tentatively offering $232.4 million of general purpose revenue bonds with a maximum yield of 6.89 percent for an issue due 2015.

headline: Philippine Rebels Say They Killed U.S. Colonel
abstract: LEAD: Communist rebels said today that they killed an American army officer on Friday because the officer was a ''direct participant'' in the Government's counterinsurgency program.

headline: Soviets Recover Two Treasures
abstract: LEAD: Raisa Gorbachev, the Soviet leader's wife, took two cultural objects back to Moscow today.

headline: Correction
abstract: LEAD: Because of an editing error, the Prospects column last week mistakenly added a phrase to the comments of Edward S. Hyman, vice chairman of C. J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc., on the course of inflation. The sentence containing his prediction should have read: ''This means that by late 1990 inflation will be back down to 3 percent.

headline: T.V.A. to Retire High-Rate Bonds
abstract: LEAD: The Tennessee Valley Authority plans to retire about $750 million of high-interest bonds and save itself $30 million in interest payments annually.

headline: Former Jordache Officer To Lead A.J.'s Jeanswear
abstract: LEAD: Russell Hartman, a former president of the jeans division of Jordache Enterprises, heads a group that has bought A. J.'s Jeanswear, an Atlanta-based jeans and sportswear company, with hopes of repeating the Jordache success.

headline: Mexico Aid Package Spurs Talk With Banks
abstract: LEAD: A $5.5 billion aid package will be provided to Mexico by the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund and Japanese banks.

headline: Western Health Gets Pacificare Bid
abstract: LEAD: Pacificare Health Systems Inc. submitted a bid for the membership and doctor contracts of Western Health Plans Inc., an ailing health maintenance company based in San Diego. Western had invited Pacificare to bid. The companies said they would meet on Friday to discuss the offer, the terms of which were not made public.

headline: EXECUTIVES
abstract: LEAD: * Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette, the investment brokerage firm, said A. Andrew Levison, John M. McMahon and Andrew J. Nathanson had joined the firm as managing directors.

headline: S.A.S. to Buy Stake In Hotels Group
abstract: LEAD: Scandinavian Airlines System has agreed to pay Japan's giant Saison Group $500 million for a 40 percent stake in its Inter-Continental Hotels group. Saison, a retail and leisure conglomerate with annual sales of nearly $30 billion, bought the Inter-Continental group, which has 106 hotels, from Grand Metropolitan P.L.C.

headline: Tunisia Choice on Mine
abstract: LEAD: The Tunisian Government's Office of Mines said today that it had selected the West German company Metallgesellschaft A.G. to be its partner in developing a zinc mine in the northwestern part of the country. The mine, to be about 85 miles southwest of Tunis, has reserves of six million metric tons of ore containing 12 percent zinc and 3 percent lead, said Mohsen Zrelli, the head of the office.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * American Capital Corp., Miami, a savings and loan holding company, said Robert Marlin had resigned as chairman.

headline: McCall's Sale to Diamandis Expected
abstract: LEAD: Reeling from a sharp decline in advertising revenue, McCall's magazine is being sold to Diamandis Communications Inc., perhaps as early as this weekend, magazine industry executives said yesterday.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; America West's Chief Seeks Growth in East
abstract: LEAD: An executive who has long looked far ahead, Edward R. Beauvais, the founder, chairman and chief executive of America West Airlines, has been broadening his horizons since he conceived of the company in 1981. Last week, the Phoenix-based airline indicated that it is looking east, offering $415 million for the Eastern Airlines shuttle and topping a $365 million bid by the New York developer Donald J.

headline: Citibank Loan-Loss Plan
abstract: LEAD: Citibank announced yesterday that it would shield its shareholders' profits from losses on loans to Argentina, by deducting the losses from reserves and not replenishing the reserves.

headline: Bhutto Moves to Strengthen Hold on Pakistan
abstract: LEAD: Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto is apparently moving to shake off military holdovers from the days of her late predecessor, Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, before her trip to the United States in early June.

headline: Rise in Fund Yields Eases
abstract: LEAD: Yields offered by money market mutual funds were up for the week that ended yesterday, but for the second straight week the increase was less than in the week before.

headline: Business and Health; A.T.&T.'s Effort To Curb Costs
abstract: LEAD: IN bargaining that could set a pattern for many large corporations with strong unions, the American Telephone and Telegraph Company is calling on its employees to pay a larger share of their health-care expenses.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Bangor Hydro-Electric Co., Bangor, Me., a utility, named Robert S. Briggs president and chief operating officer.

headline: 13 Are Charged With Treason In Failed Coup in Guatemala
abstract: LEAD: A military tribunal indicted 13 officers today on charges of treason and rebellion in connection with a failed attempt last week to topple the civilian Government.

headline: Real Estate; High-Tech Offices Rise In Jersey City
abstract: LEAD: FROM the outside, the 14-story building nearing completion on Newport Drive and Washington Boulevard in Jersey City differs little from the other commercial structures that have sprouted on the west bank of the Hudson River in recent years.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST: SATURDAY APRIL 1, 1989
abstract: LEAD:  The Economy

headline: MADRID ENVOY DIES IN BEIRUT SHELLING
abstract: LEAD: The Spanish Ambassador to Lebanon and 16 other people were killed today as the capital went through yet another day of heavy shelling by warring Christian and Muslim factions.

headline: Northwest Air Picks a Buyer
abstract: LEAD: Northwest Airlines accepted a $3.64 billion offer from a group organized by Alfred Checchi, a 41-year-old Los Angeles businessman. The bidding group includes KLM Royal Dutch Airlines and the Elders beer company of Australia. Mr. Checchi said the Elders investment was passive but KLM would try to link its European routes and Northwest's service to Asia.

headline: GBP Industries
abstract: LEAD: GBP Industries announced that it had agreed to sell all of its outstanding stock to Sullivan Graphics Inc. Terms were not disclosed. GBP Industries, which is privately held and based in Buffalo, owns seven printing operations in the United States and Canada that produce high-volume products. It had revenues of $472 million in 1988.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Allied Security Inc., Pittsburgh, a security guard service, received an acquisition bid of $53 a share from a group led by the company's chairman, Neal H. Holmes, and its president, Steven B. Stein.

headline: China Concerns Face Inquiry
abstract: LEAD: The Chinese authorities have recommended fining five state-owned companies, including one founded by the eldest son of the leader Deng Xiaoping, for profiteering, the Economic Reporter magazine said.

headline: A Health-Care Taboo Is Broken
abstract: LEAD: Facing at least $5 billion in employee medical costs this year, many automobile industry executives acknowledge that their efforts to control costs have failed, and they are calling for drastic changes in the way the nation pays for health care.

headline: A.T.&T. to Buy More of Sun Stock
abstract: LEAD: The American Telephone and Telegraph Company, which already holds a 17.1 percent stake in Sun Microsystems Inc., said it had been notified by Sun that it would be required to buy three million additional Sun common shares for a total of $75 million.

headline: Japanese Takeover Bid
abstract: LEAD: General Ceramics Inc. of Haskell, N.J., will divest itself of units involved in nuclear weapons production to meet objections raised by the Bush Administration to a takeover by the Tokuyama Soda Company of Tokyo, Administration officials said today. According to the officials, the Energy Department is working with the company on a divestment plan, but details were unavailable.

headline: Hussein and Mubarak Discuss Israel's Plan
abstract: LEAD: King Hussein of Jordan met with President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt over a Muslim Ramadan supper here tonight to formulate a common response to Israel's newest proposals on the Palestinian issue, including elections in the occupied territories.

headline: F.C.C. Policy Assisting Minorities Is Overturned
abstract: LEAD: A Federal appeals court today ruled unconstitutional a Federal Communications Commission policy intended to increase opportunities for members of minority groups to own radio and television stations.

headline: Japan Takes a Leading Role In the Third-World Debt Crisis
abstract: LEAD: Cautiously but with rising self-confidence, Japan has begun to assert its economic leadership and speak with a louder voice on the debt crisis crushing the world's poor nations.

headline: 2,000 Protest in Beijing At Public Security Office
abstract: LEAD: About 2,000 students and workers protested in front of the Public Security Ministry tonight, and three union leaders were released after two days of interrogation.

headline: Santa Fe Loses Round in Court
abstract: LEAD: The Santa Fe Pacific Corporation said Friday that a United States District Court judge had denied its motions to set a new trial and to overturn a $1.04 billion jury award against it in the coal slurry case involving Energy Transportation Systems Inc.

headline: Convex Profit Doubles
abstract: LEAD: The Convex Computer Corporation, a maker of mini-supercomputers, said Tuesday that its earnings doubled in the first quarter, to $2.3 million, or 12 cents a share, from $1.1 million, or 6 cents a share, in the corresponding quarter a year ago. Sales for the first quarter jumped 50.7 percent, to $33.3 million from $22.1 million, because of increased demand for the company's C200 line of supercomputers.

headline: British Spending Up 3.1%
abstract: LEAD: Consumer spending in Britain rose 3.1 percent in March, in line with economists' forecasts and matching February's gain, official figures showed today. The report cheered officials, as any significant gain from February's levels would have raised the possibility of further interest rate increases to choke off inflation, analysts said.

headline: A.T.&.T. Set To Reduce Rates by 0.9%
abstract: LEAD: The American Telephone and Telegraph Company said yesterday that it would cut its long-distance rates an average of nine-tenths of 1 percent on July 1 to comply with a new method of rate regulation adopted by the Federal Communications Commission in March.

headline: Pentagon Fraud Case Goes to Jury
abstract: LEAD: A Federal jury began deliberations today in the first trial to result from the Government's ''Ill Wind'' investigation of Pentagon procurement fraud.

headline: Treasury Issues Move Upward
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury securities moved higher in fairly active trading yesterday, propelled by weaker-than-expected economic data and rumors that a coming report from the nation's purchasing managers will show that economic conditions worsened in April.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Alleghany Corp. has filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission for $55 million of subordinated debentures due in 2014 through Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. The debentures are exchangeable for American Express Co. common stock owned by Alleghany.

headline: Former Piedmont Head Pushes Bid for Eastern
abstract: LEAD: William R. Howard, former head of Piedmont Airlines, is not holding back in the effort to put together his own reorganization plan for Eastern Airlines.

headline: Chairman at Thomson
abstract: LEAD: Alain Gomez, the chairman of the state-owned electronics company Thomson S.A. and its Thomson-CSF unit, has been reappointed by the French Government to a three-year term, to expire in 1992.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; D.F. King Owner Moves To Position of Chairman
abstract: LEAD: D. F. King & Co., a privately held financial communications company that solicits shareholders' proxies and advises corporate management in takeover battles, has elevated its longtime senior executive and owner, John W. Cornwell, to the position of chairman.

headline: Citicorp Rates Up
abstract: LEAD: Interest rates at Citicorp's weekly auction of 91-day and 182-day commercial paper rose for the first time in three weeks. The company sold $50 million in 91-day paper at an average rate of 9.7245 percent, up from 9.65 percent last week, and $50 million in 182-day paper at an average rate of 9.635 percent, up from 9.51 percent.

headline: 8 States Plan Canada Office
abstract: LEAD: Eight states bordering the Great Lakes plan to open a permanent office in Canada to take advantage of what they consider an improved climate for cross-border cooperation in tourism, economic development and the environment.

headline: Chevron Sale
abstract: LEAD: The Chevron Corporation said that it would accept bids for its oil and gas exploration and producing properties in Spain and that it had recently distributed material about a possible offer to some potential buyers. The Spanish properties consist of 3 oilfields and 14 offshore exploration permits and are being offered as a single package.

headline: Cocoa Prices Fall Sharply Amid Talk of Global Surplus
abstract: LEAD: Cocoa prices tumbled on both sides of the Atlantic today amid talk of a global surplus and forecasts of a record crop in 1989.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; People
abstract: LEAD: * Richard H. Pell has joined Wellington International advertising, a division of Euro-American Communications, as executive vice president.

headline: In Mexico, Drug Roots Run Deep
abstract: LEAD: The most notorious drug-trafficking figure in Mexico, Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo, is finally behind bars. But the culture from which he emerged, a virulent combination of violence and vast illegal wealth, remains deeply rooted here in his home city and state.

headline: Careers; Difficulties For Women Engineers
abstract: LEAD: ''THINGS haven't changed much for women in engineering in recent years,'' said Helen Hollein, a chemical engineering professor at Manhattan College. She made the comment last week at a discusson about women engineers at the Electro-89 convention in the Javits Convention Center.

headline: U.S. and Moscow Agree to Exchange Diplomacy Experts
abstract: LEAD: The United States and the Soviet Union announced an agreement today that will permit the exchange of international-affairs specialists and diplomatic personnel for the first time.

headline: Government Unions Put Polish Pact in Doubt
abstract: LEAD: On the eve of formal ceremonies to sign accords between the Government and the independent union Solidarity, the Government's own official unions refused tonight to accept a part of the agreement that Solidarity considers essential.

headline: Solidarity Says Warsaw Is Playing Campaign Tricks
abstract: LEAD: Solidarity accused the Communist authorities today of using dirty tricks to upset its election campaign and of seeking to drive a wedge between the newly legalized union and its most ardent supporters.

headline: Patents; Replacement Of Quigg Expected
abstract: LEAD: The Secretary of Commerce, Robert A. Mosbacher, is said to have recommended that Harry F. Manbeck, head of the General Electric Company's patent department, replace Donald J. Quigg as Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks.

headline: In Washington, Just a Hint of the Alliance's Angst
abstract: LEAD: In London, Bonn, Paris and Rome, indeed right across Western Europe, politicians and large segments of the public are hotly debating the new rifts in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization that West Germany has laid bare for all to see.

headline: Market Place; Investor's Bet Is Against Horses
abstract: LEAD: IN horse racing, there is no such thing as a sure thing. The same uncertainty surrounds Hollywood Park, a venerable race track that may become a takeover target.

headline: Prospects; Unemployment's Tiny Fall
abstract: LEAD: The unemployment statistics for May, which were released Friday, showed the rate dropped by one-tenth of one percentage point to 5.1 percent. But while unemployment dropped, the number of new jobs created in May was 101,000, less than half of April's total. During May, 18,000 jobs in manufacturing were lost along with 14,000 in construction.

headline: Senegal Strife Leaves Air of Menace
abstract: LEAD: For two weeks, the tranquillity of this West African country has taken on an air of menace as thousands of Mauritanians, fearing attack by their Senegalese hosts here, have fled or gone into hiding.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Orangina's New Image: Adults Only
abstract: LEAD: CAN Orangina do for the soft-drink industry what Heineken did for the beer business?

headline: Up in the Air
abstract: LEAD: To the Editor:

headline: Cineplex Bidders Sought
abstract: LEAD: The two senior officers of the Cineplex Odeon Corporation said today that they were seeking individual partners or corporations that might be interested in bidding for control of the motion picture and theater company. In a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Garth H. Drabinsky, chairman of Cineplex Odeon, and Myron I.

headline: Upheaval in China; From Asian Neighbors, It's Silence and Anxiety
abstract: LEAD: Asian governments are largely keeping silent on the upheaval in China, waiting to see whether Beijing will move toward further democracy or repression.

headline: Treasury Notes and Bonds Higher
abstract: LEAD: Treasury note and bond prices closed moderately higher yesterday, after late selling cut some earlier gains in half. Dealers attributed much of the late selloff to the usual squaring of accounts before a long Fourth of July holiday weekend.

headline: Debt Request To Citibank
abstract: LEAD: Five South American countries have called on Citibank to reverse its seizure of $80 million from Ecuador for arrears in the payments of its foreign debt.

headline: 'USA' Show Creator Quits
abstract: LEAD: Steve Friedman, who created ''USA Today: The Television Show,'' has resigned, effective May 29, as president of GTG East, which produces the program.

headline: Head of Landstar Unit Appointed Parent's Chief
abstract: LEAD: Jeffrey C. Crowe, who built one of the trucking companies of Landstar System Inc. almost from scratch into a business with $130 million in annual sales, has been named president and chief executive of Landstar.

headline: INVESTING; The Highest-Yielding Fund
abstract: LEAD: For several weeks the Dreyfus Corporation's Worldwide Dollar Money Market Fund has had the highest yield of any money fund tracked by Donoghue's Money Fund Report. It recently had a compounded yield of 10.89 percent.

headline: Toiling Teen-agers
abstract: LEAD: To the Editor:

headline: CHINA'S DUAL VIEW OF WESTERN TIES
abstract: LEAD: Near the end of the evening news programs here for the last few days, some people identified as ''foreign investors'' have been shown at meetings with Chinese partners. The investors express their confidence that after the army's ''calming'' of the recent ''counterrevolutionary disturbance'' in Beijing, business can proceed more or less as usual.

headline: MIM to Vote Stake For Oak Dissidents
abstract: LEAD: MIM Ltd., the British investment firm that is the largest shareholder in Oak Industries, said it would vote its 24.9 percent stake in favor of the dissident group waging a proxy fight for control of the San Diego-based manufacturer of electronic communications equipment. The group is led by Roderick H.

headline: Gibraltar Payment On Bonds Delayed
abstract: LEAD: The Gibraltar Financial Corporation, parent company of Gibraltar Savings and Loan of Beverly Hills, Calif., said it would not make a $1.02 million interest payment due today to bondholders. headline: Alternative Weeklies on the Rise
abstract: LEAD: After more than 50 years of consolidation, competition is rushing back into the newspaper industry in the form of urban weeklies that describe themselves as alternative publications.

headline: A Data Processing Unit At American Express
abstract: LEAD: The American Express Company said yesterday that it had formed a company that will offer computerized financial transactions and will compete in some markets with data processing giants like the Electronic Data Systems Corporation and Automatic Data Processing Inc.

headline: Bigger Empire Is Aim Of Goldman Financial
abstract: LEAD: David L. Goldman, starting from close to scratch, has built up a small industrial empire in the last three years and now is seeking to enlarge it with a $120 million offer to buy the Gleason Corporation, a leading maker of gear equipment.

headline: Greenspan Leaves Hospital
abstract: LEAD: The chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, Alan Greenspan, was released from a hospital this morning after being treated overnight for heat exhaustion, a Fed spokesman said today.

headline: ISRAEL ARMY EXPELS EIGHT PALESTINIANS
abstract: LEAD: The Israeli Army deported eight Palestinians to Lebanon today. But for the first time Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told the deportees that they might be allowed to return, under certain circumstances.

headline: Bangladesh Cyclone Kills 84
abstract: LEAD: A cyclone that tore across Bangladesh and eastern India on Saturday killed at least 84 people and left more than half a million homeless, officials and news reports said today. Tens of thousands of mud and straw huts were blown away during the storm, which was accompanied by winds of up to 85 miles per hour, they said.

headline: Young in China Being Stirred By an Old-Time Christianity
abstract: LEAD: Her hair still glistening with holy water, her spirit soaring with excitement, Lu Yun, newly baptized, brimmed with the kind of reverent ardor that leaves Communist officials queasy.

headline: Texaco to Change Gasoline Additive
abstract: LEAD: Texaco Inc. said it would change the additive package in its gasoline sold at 18,500 service stations, with chemicals designed to clean fuel injectors without reducing octane - and therefore performance. The company's System 3 gasoline was introduced in Houston, Dallas, Austin and San Antonio on May 22 and will be sold in Los Angeles next week and New York the week of July 17, the company said.

headline: Retail Sales Up by Only 0.1% in May
abstract: LEAD: Sluggish automobile and department store purchases slowed the pace of retail sales in May to an increase of one-tenth of 1 percent, the Government reported today. Analysts said they did not expect much improvement soon.

headline: Mazda and Ford In Venture Talks
abstract: LEAD: The Mazda Motor Corporation, the Japanese car maker, is discussing with its American partner, the Ford Motor Company, a venture in Europe, a top Mazda official said. Mazda's United States president, Osamu Nobuto, said a decision should be made by the end of 1990.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Ambase Corp. of New York, a financial services concern, named Bruce W. Bean executive vice president.

headline: Possible Heir for the Top Job Appointed by Ohio Mattress
abstract: LEAD: The Ohio Mattress Company, one of the world's largest makers of bedding, said yesterday that Malcolm Candlish, former chief executive of the Samsonite Corporation, had been named president and chief operating officer.

headline: Chief Resigns From Matilda
abstract: LEAD: Sandra Yates, the president and chief executive of Matilda Publications Inc., which owns Ms. and Sassy magazines, resigned last week to ''work on other publishing projects,'' the company said.

headline: New Fall in Long-Term Rates Seen
abstract: LEAD: Long-term interest rates, already down to levels not seen since April 1987, could fall further in coming weeks because of strong foreign and domestic demand for bonds, money market economists said.

headline: A Slower Pace for Economy
abstract: LEAD: In a report viewed as encouraging, the G.N.P. for the first quarter grew at a 4.3 percent pace, not the 5.5 percent initially estimated. Page D1.

headline: Two Palestinians Slain In Clash With Troops
abstract: LEAD: Army troops fatally shot two Palestinian teen-agers today, Arab reports said, and hundreds of Israelis screaming ''Death to the Arabs!'' stoned Arab-owned cars in a protest over the slaying of a soldier.

headline: Prime Computer Seeking Suitor
abstract: LEAD: Prime Computer Inc., fighting a $966 million bid from a much smaller rival, is promoting its lucrative European operations to entice a friendly suitor, the company's president, Anthony Craig, said in an interview. MAI Basic Four Inc., a Tustin, Calif., company controlled by Bennett LeBow, the financier, has pursued Prime since November.

headline: Defector to Moscow Is Dead; Work for K.G.B. Is Lauded
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union today announced the death of a United States Navy defector, who was described as having played a vital role as an intelligence agent for the K.G.B.

headline: What If Airlines Banned Laptops?
abstract: LEAD: The plastic explosive that destroyed Pan Am's Flight 103 over Scotland last year was hidden in a portable radio. Some Government and airline safety officials have concluded that it might just as easily have been concealed in a portable computer or another small electronic device.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Foote, Cone Profit
abstract: LEAD: Foote, Cone & Belding Communications said yesterday its first-quarter earnings were flat compared with the corresponding period a year ago. The Chicago-based company reported net income of $2.4 million, or 24 cents a share, in the first three months of 1989, compared with $2.39 million, or 28 cents a share, in 1988.

headline: Poland Bars 8 Key Communists From Runoff Vote
abstract: LEAD: Eight members of the Commmunist Party Politburo, shaken by defeat in the national elections earlier this month, have been barred from runoff balloting on Sunday, the Government said today.

headline: Atlanta Investor Gets $2 Million
abstract: LEAD: An Atlanta businessman has been awarded $2 million by a three-member arbitration panel of the National Association of Securities Dealers in connection with a complex stock options program under which he said he lost more than $1.7 million in four days.

headline: A Legal Uproar Over Dimples and Grooves
abstract: LEAD: ''Golf is a game about suffering and despair, interspersed with glimmers of hope,'' opined Frank Hannigan, a contributing editor of Golf Magazine and former president of the United States Golf Association. ''It can be alleviated by going into a store and buying something.''

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; Chief of Halliburton Becomes Its Chairman
abstract: LEAD: Taking steps to provide for an orderly succession of its senior management, the Halliburton Company has named its president and chief executive, Thomas H. Cruikshank, to be its chairman.

headline: FEUDING SETS TONE IN SOVIET CONGRESS
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union today struggled to give birth to a new kind of government in a process that laid bare bitter divisions of class, geography, nationality and outlook.

headline: NATO Proposal 'Disappoints' Shevardnadze
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Foreign Minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, said today that he was ''disappointed'' with the Atlantic alliance's proposal for opening negotiations on short-range missiles only after a conventional arms accord was completed and being put into effect.

headline: GATT Warns of Tensions
abstract: LEAD: Tensions have increased in international trade and the commitment of governments to free-trade talks is facing its ''sternest test,'' the organization sponsoring the talks said today.

headline: Cray Is Said to Weigh Making Big Changes
abstract: LEAD: Just a month after the Control Data Corporation withdrew from the supercomputer business, Cray Research Inc. is reported to be considering a variety of restructuring options, which may include selling or splitting the company.

headline: Broad Support Sen for Incentives on New TV Technology
abstract: LEAD: The Bush Administration can expect wide support in both Congress and industry for its anticipated proposal to relax antitrust laws to help American companies gain a foothold in high-definition television and other budding technologies, lawmakers and industry executives said today.

headline: Pepperell Job Rise
abstract: LEAD: West Point-Pepperell will put plants in Alabama, Georgia and Texas on seven-day workweeks in an expansion that is expected to create 330 new jobs. The textile company also plans to buy $40 million in new equipment for its bed products group, Pepperell's parent company, Chicago-based Farley Inc., announced.

headline: NAMIBIA STANDOFF OVER GUERRILLAS
abstract: LEAD: A standoff between South Africa and the United Nations developed here today in the rugged bush over the disposition of the first Namibian guerrillas facing return to Angola.

headline: SOLIDARITY REINSTATED
abstract: LEAD: The leaders of Solidarity signed accords with the Government today restoring the banned union's legal status and providing for the first free and open elections in this country since World War II.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Affiliated Publications Inc., Boston, a publishing and broadcasting company, promoted Arthur F. Kingsbury to executive vice president and William B. Huff to chief financial officer.

headline: Italy Awaits Bush Nominee With Misgivings
abstract: LEAD: Headlines here refer to him as ''the ambassador of dirty words,'' and Government officials complain privately, and newspapers publicly, that his appointment is proof of the low regard that the United States Government has for Italy.

headline: U.S. Issues Steady in Dull Trading
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds were little changed yesterday at the close of what many market participants said was the slowest session of the year.

headline: Debt Relief For Farmers
abstract: LEAD: The Government's chief farm lender may lose as much as $4 billion as it plows through a backlog of $9 billion in bad debts stemming from the farm crisis of the early and mid-1980's, agency officials said today.

headline: STUDENTS RENEW CALL FOR CHANGE IN BEIJING MARCH
abstract: LEAD: About 100,000 people on foot and on bicycles streamed through the capital today to demand more democracy and the resignation of Prime Minister Li Peng. The police and soldiers made no move to interfere despite martial law restrictions and the Government's strict warnings against demonstrations.

headline: Stocks That Rose in Quarter Outnumbered Losers 2 to 1
abstract: LEAD: Stocks advanced in the first quarter in a wide array of industries, including airline operators, software makers and energy companies.

headline: Anglican Heads Try to Defuse Women's Issue
abstract: LEAD: The heads of the world's Anglican churches, meeting last week in Cyprus, have endorsed a report aimed at preventing the question of consecrating women as bishops from creating new divisions among the 70 million Anglicans.

headline: Stock Surge Moderates as Dow Gains 7.51
abstract: LEAD: The stock market moved higher yesterday, building on a rally that since Friday has pushed the Dow Jones industrial average to its highest level since the October 1987 crash. But the surge moderated, even as trading volume remained strong.

headline: President Is Named For Vanguard Group
abstract: LEAD: John J. Brennan, who is 34 years old, was named president of 29 companies yesterday.

headline: Texas Foreclosure Plan
abstract: LEAD: In a move that could raise the cost of Federal bailout programs for the state's financial institutions, Texas legislators are considering making it more difficult for lenders to recover losses in delinquent loans. Page D1.

headline: Your Money; Planning Ahead To Retire Early
abstract: LEAD: The majority of Americans would like to retire early, but few have done the serious retirement planning that would enable them to do so comfortably, a survey by Merrill Lynch & Company shows.

headline: USAir Orders Jets
abstract: LEAD: USAir Group Inc. has ordered 18 Boeing 737 jets and taken options on 36 more in a transaction valued at up to $1.7 billion, the airline announced. The aircraft will be in the 737-300, 737-400 and 737-500 series. Deliveries of the 18 firm orders will be one a month in 1991 and two monthly in the first quarter of 1992.

headline: KOREA CHIEF URGES CALM AFTER CLASH
abstract: LEAD: President Roh Tae Woo of South Korea urged ''steadfast patience'' tonight after the deaths of six riot police officers in a clash with radical students earlier in the day. But he warned that he would consider invoking ''emergency measures'' if violence recurred.

headline: 3 Airlines Say Profits Surged
abstract: LEAD: The parent companies of United and Delta airlines reported record first-quarter earnings yesterday, a sign that much of the airline industry is entering a boom period. Fares and traffic are rising while fuel and labor costs have been relatively steady.

headline: Mount Gay Rum Goes To Margeotes Fertitta
abstract: LEAD: Margeotes Fertitta & Weiss has become the first beneficiary of Remy Martin et Compagnie S.A.'s acquisition of ''21'' Brands Inc. earlier this year. The agency yesterday gained the account of Mount Gay rum, part of the ''21'' package.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; WPP Group Acquires
abstract: LEAD: Through its subsidiaries, J. Walter Thompson and Hill & Knowlton, the WPP Group yesterday acquired two Austrian marketing companies. J. Walter Thompson bought Ernst Haupt-Stummer, Austria's second-oldest full-service advertising agency after Thompson's own Austrian branch. The agency will be merged with Thompson.

headline: Price Riot in Jordan
abstract: LEAD: Riots over price increases erupted in Maan in southern Jordan today and at least 17 people were injured as some 4,000 people attacked shops and set cars on fire, a hospital source said. Security forces opened fire to disperse the demonstrators, the source said. Reached by telephone from Amman, the source said 17 people were being treated at a hospital in Maan.

headline: CATHOLIC CHURCH IN PANAMA ASSAILS NORIEGA'S REGIME
abstract: LEAD: Panama's Roman Catholic Church today released a blistering attack on the regime of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, questioning his moral authority to govern and inviting the military to disobey repressive orders.

headline: The World Catches Takeover Fever
abstract: LEAD: The financial revolution of the 1980's has given us a glimpse of a truly borderless global village of finance and business. The results of these tumultuous times have become manifest in four major trends that have affected all businesses in the 1980's and that will continue to affect them in the decade ahead.

headline: Hasbro Adopts 'Poison Pill'
abstract: LEAD: Hasbro Inc., the toy manufacturer, said today that it had adopted an anti-takeover measure.

headline: Experts Divided On Jobs in the 90's
abstract: LEAD: THE nation's unemployment rate, 4.9 percent, is at its lowest point in the last 15 years. But at the same time the number of new jobs has fallen to its lowest monthly level since last August. What do these figures portend for the nation's workplace in the months and years ahead? How will the world of work change in the decade before the 21st century?

headline: Market Place; Standouts Among Bank-Run Funds
abstract: LEAD: STOCK mutual funds managed by bank trust departments underperformed the general stock market by a slight margin in the first quarter, according to statistics compiled by CDA Investment Technologies Inc.

headline: Talking Deals; Metropolitan's Bond Covenants
abstract: LEAD: FOR nearly four years the Metropolitan Life Insurance Company has insisted that any company that wanted to borrow money from it agree to repay the loans immediately if the company changed hands.

headline: Pickens's Battle With Koito
abstract: LEAD: T. Boone Pickens, the Texas oilman, said today that he would continue to press for a seat on the board of the Koito Manufacturing Company, of which he owns 20.2 percent, in a battle to open up Japan's financial system.

headline: 12 Bodies Found in Sri Lanka
abstract: LEAD: The charred bodies of 12 suspected rebels were found overnight in different parts of Sri Lanka, the police and residents said today. No group claimed responsibility for the killings.

headline: Nicaragua Inflation Cut
abstract: LEAD: Nicaragua's inflation rate, one of the highest in the world, declined sharply in March, according to official figures published this week. Consumer price inflation fell to a monthly rate of 20 percent in March from 46 percent in February. Inflation reached a high of 126.6 percent in December, falling to 91.8 percent in January, when the Government put austerity measures into effect.

headline: Dollar Rides Rising Tide
abstract: LEAD: The remarkable rise in the dollar's value this month seems to have been the result of several events coming together to set off a rally that then took on a life of its own.

headline: In Quest for Democracy, a Mini-City Is Born
abstract: LEAD: A few hundred yards from the center of Chinese bureaucracy, where the Communist Party leadership is engaged in a bitter power struggle, a smaller group of less experienced bureaucrats on Tiananmen Square is building its own society, a virtual city of protest.

headline: MCI Gets Contract
abstract: LEAD: The MCI Communications Corporation said the Westinghouse Electric Corporation had given it a five-year contract worth $75 million to $100 million to expand and enhance its voice and digital communications network. The U S Sprint Communications Company and the American Telephone and Telegraph Company also bid for the contract, MCI said.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Three Leave Doyle Graf In Protest
abstract: LEAD: Three top executives of Doyle Graf Raj walked out on Friday to form an independent advertising agency, accusing Doyle Graf's chief executive of trying to find a buyer for the small New York agency despite an earlier agreement to sell it to them.

headline: 2 Arabs Killed as Israel Mourns Its War Dead
abstract: LEAD: Israel mourned its war dead today and Israeli troops killed an Arab youth during a Palestinian strike marking the start of the 18th month of the revolt against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.

headline: York Journal; A County by a New Name Doesn't Smell as Sweet

Roman and Elizabethan ruins are excavated and covered up again by commercial construction, and the elegant Wren spires of the City of London are overwhelmed by a hodgepodge of undistinguished commercial office buildings.

headline: Parties to Namibia Pact Discuss Timetable
abstract: LEAD: Negotiations to put Namibia's stalled independence timetable back on track opened today near this border town, where the first incursions by guerrillas infiltrating from Angola set off bitter fighting a month and a half ago.

abstract: LEAD: The NCNB Corporation said there was ''no merit'' to assertions by the Citizens and Southern Corporation that a Government-assisted bank deal in Texas enabled NCNB to make a $2.4 billion bid for Citizens and Southern. headline: India Trade Dispute Brings Austerity to Nepal
abstract: LEAD: The Nepalese Government, digging in for a long siege in a trade war with India that is being seen here as a test of Nepalese sovereignty, has introduced austerity measures and started reordering its development plans, officials here say.

headline: Port Authority Is Offering $100 Million in Serial Bonds
abstract: LEAD: The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey yesterday offered $100 million of bonds at competitive bid.

headline: Plastic Trash: 'Silk Purses' Sought

abstract: LEAD: One of the most sought-after publications in Nigeria is the May issue of an American magazine, Ebony.

Jacobs, the Minneapolis investor, might make a new offer for Avon Products Inc., the direct-selling cosmetics company based in New York, Avon's stock climbed $1.125 yesterday, closing at $35.875, on the New York Stock Exchange. abstract: LEAD: The president of the Hungarian Communist Party's newly created Presidium said today that his job was to be ''first among equals'' in a ''collective leadership'' that will ''guide and determine party policy.''

abstract: LEAD: At an immigration checkpoint a few miles from the Mexico-Guatemala border, a group of two dozen Salvadorans, Nicaraguans, Guatemalans and Hondurans waited forlornly one recent morning as Mexican immigration officials finished their interrogation and prepared to put them aboard the bus that would deport them.

headline: Two Issues Set By Londontown
abstract: LEAD: The Londontown Holdings Corporation and its Londontown Corporation yesterday announced the offering of two new issues through Kidder, Peabody & Company as sole underwriter.

abstract: LEAD: Twelve Lebanese were reported killed and 15 wounded today as Muslim and Christian forces continued artillery and rocket battles for a third week.

abstract: LEAD: The Treasury's schedule of new issues includes today's regular auction of new three-month and six-month bills. On Wednesday the Government will auction $8.75 billion of new two-year notes and on Thursday it will auction $7.5 billion of new five-year notes.

abstract: LEAD: Lord & Taylor, which plans to take over four store sites of Hahne & Company in New Jersey, said it would also establish units in two other Hahne stores, in Eatontown and Trenton. Hahne is being phased out by the May Department Stores Company, which also operates Lord & Taylor.

abstract: LEAD: Frank Lorenzo, the chairman of the Texas Air Corporation, reaffirmed yesterday that Eastern Airlines was no longer for sale and that he planned to rebuild the airline with nonunion employees over the coming months.

But he also defended Moscow's ''balanced'' response, asserting that the information was still vague and that the priority was to safeguard the fledgling Chinese program of change.

abstract: LEAD: The gradual slowing of the American economy is a two-edged sword that will both help and hurt developing countries, a World Bank affiliate said today.

abstract: LEAD: A prophet is not without honor save in his own country, so it isn't surprising that former Chancellor Helmut Schmidt of West Germany and former Prime Minister Edward Heath of Britain both think that Europe could have achieved a single market long before 1992 - if only people had listened to them.

abstract: LEAD: President Bush scored a political victory today as the Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted to recommend the confirmation of Donald P. Gregg as Ambassador to South Korea, despite questions about Mr. Gregg's role in the Iran-contra affair.

abstract: LEAD: Investcorp, the Bahrain investment bank, said yesterday in London that it had acquired a 50 percent interest in Gucci America Inc. in addition to the 50 percent already held in Guccio Gucci S.p.A., the principal Gucci leather goods company based in Florence. abstract: LEAD: Confirming reports of last week, the Ford Motor Company today named Allan D. Gilmour executive vice president in charge of corporate staffs, making him the likely successor of Donald E. Petersen, the company's chairman and chief executive.

abstract: LEAD: Peter V. Ueberroth said yesterday that it would be difficult for a potential buyer of Eastern Airlines to reach an agreement that would satisfy both the airline's striking unions and the creditors committee in the carrier's bankruptcy case.

abstract: LEAD: Linden Court, a 30-story condominium tower, will begin rising this summer on an eight-acre tract opposite Bushnell Park because city officials here are now using a carrot-and-stick approach to encourage residential development downtown.

abstract: LEAD: When Time Inc. announced last week that it was bidding for Warner Communiciations Inc., officials of the companies were asked whether the lucrative contract of Warner's chief executive, Steven J. Ross, had been modified from the terms set in the earlier merger agreement of the companies.

abstract: LEAD: The Lomas Financial Corporation said today that it had agreed to sell its credit card bank subsidiary for $500 million in cash and preferred stock to an investor group led by Merrill Lynch Capital Partners. The price is the highest ever paid for a credit card business.

headline: 4 Arrested In Computer Export Case
abstract: LEAD: The United States Customs Service said today that it had made four arrests and seized $1.8 million worth of computers from a nationwide smuggling ring that has been sending high-technology equipment to Eastern bloc countries.

abstract: LEAD: Borrowers who opted for adjustable-rate mortgages knew they were taking a chance. But for years the risks seemed relatively slight as interest rates on their loans remained below those of conventional fixed mortgages. No longer.  Some holders of older adjustable-rate mortgages are seeing their rates jump to more than 12 percent, while the rates on new fixed loans are hovering around 11.

headline: A World View In 4 Speeches
abstract: LEAD: President Bush's foreign-policy speech today was the last of four before a Western summit meeting next week.

abstract: LEAD: A classified study by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's military commander states that the alliance can significantly cut the size of its nuclear arsenal if it deploys a successor to old Lance short-range missiles and modernizes other atomic weapons, according to Administration officials.

headline: Market Place; Tenneco Deals Called Unlikely
abstract: LEAD: TENNECO INC. was a favored punching bag on Wall Street a year ago, branded as a lumbering conglomerate that was too tolerant of losses in an age of leaner, sharper competitors. abstract: LEAD: The United States accused the South-West Africa People's Organization today of violating accords for the independence of Namibia by provoking the worst fighting inside the territory in the guerrillas' struggle for self-government.

abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury securities jumped in light trading yesterday, helped by favorable technical conditions as well as a strong performance by the dollar.

headline: An Israeli Settler Is Arrested In Fatal Clash on West Bank
abstract: LEAD: The Israeli authorities have arrested a Jewish settler suspected of involvement in a clash between settlers and Palestinians in Hebron that left one man dead last week, the police said today.

abstract: LEAD: The leading trading nations have flashed a green light for final bargaining in the postwar period's eighth and most ambitious set of talks to lower trade barriers.

abstract: LEAD: America West Airlines Inc., a growing regional airline making a push into East Coast markets, was a big winner today in a Government lottery for airline slots vacated because of the Eastern Airlines strike.

abstract: LEAD: Joseph E. Antonini, chairman of the K Mart Corporation, said the company's earnings for the current quarter would be less than a year earliier. K Mart, based in Troy, Mich., is the nation's second-largest retailer after Sears, Roebuck.

abstract: LEAD: The General Motors Corporation posted robust first-quarter earnings of $1.55 billion today, a 42 percent increase from a year earlier. Revenue in the quarter rose 12 percent, to $29.6 billion.

abstract: LEAD: Every day, hundreds of Bir Zeit University students disguise their textbooks, talk their way through army checkpoints and sneak off to secret classes in church basements, clubs and professors' homes.

headline: French Peace Effort in Lebanon: Few Results, at High Cost
abstract: LEAD: For the last three weeks, France has been embroiled in a solitary and somewhat quixotic diplomatic campaign to halt the murderous shelling in Lebanon, but so far it has generated only tepid international support and antagonized Syria.

headline: Broadcasts Show Widespread Unrest
abstract: LEAD: Chinese radio broadcasts monitored by the United States Government report turmoil and unrest in many provinces as students and other citizens protest the Government's crackdown on demonstrators in Beijing.

abstract: LEAD: A Federal judge today issued a preliminary injunction to keep MCorp's bankruptcy case in the courts and out of regulators' control.

abstract: LEAD: Sales of new homes dropped 5.5 percent in March after plunging 10.5 percent in February, the Government reported today, as higher interest rates took their toll on the housing market.

abstract: LEAD: Camcorders, which were virtually unknown only five years ago, have become a part of everyday life in much of America, transforming the way millions of people are recording their most meaningful memories and, in the process, spawning a $2.3 billion-a-year business.

abstract: LEAD: In the power struggle that consumes Iran's ruling clergy, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's son, Ahmad, has emerged as a prime contender to inherit his father's authority.

abstract: LEAD: * Bankers Trust New York Corp., a bank holding company, appointed Richard J. Carbone controller.

headline: Syria Frees Arafat Backers After 6-Year Detention
abstract: LEAD: In a sign of improved relations with the Palestine Liberation Organization, Syria has released scores of followers of Yasir Arafat after six years' detention.

abstract: LEAD: Interest rates tumbled yesterday as prices of Treasury securities were marked up sharply on news that orders for durable goods dropped 4.2 percent in May. abstract: LEAD: Uruguyans voted today to reject an effort to overturn the amnesty granted the armed forces for political crimes committed in the 1960's and 1970's, according to projections from official returns.

abstract: LEAD: Saying it was time for Poland to become part of Europe, Lech Walesa journeyed to Rome today to seek a papal blessing for his union's new spirit of understanding with the Polish Government.

abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury securities dipped slightly in light trading yesterday despite a big drop in oil prices and a surge in the value of the dollar, developments that normally tend to be viewed favorably in the credit markets.

abstract: LEAD: * Candela Laser Corp., Wayland, Mass., a laser equipment maker, named Gerard E. Puorro chief financial officer.

abstract: LEAD: The other evening, a top official in the Finance Ministry cut short his conversation, explaining that he and his colleagues had another pressing engagement. They all had to adjourn to a nearby park to sit under the cherry blossoms, sing old songs and drink beer or sake.

abstract: LEAD: I.B.M.'s newly disclosed lead in the manufacturing of a high-capacity chip could give the computer giant a significant advantage over its domestic and international competitors at a time of transition to powerful systems that require large amounts of computer memory.

headline: MAINTAINING A DELICATE BALANCE AT ARTHUR ANDERSON
abstract: LEAD: In the early morning of March 8, 24 partners of Arthur Andersen & Company filed into the boardroom on the 35th floor of Andersen's world headquarters here. The men, who make up the Board of Partners at the accounting and consulting firm, were choosing a new chief executive, and the matter could not have been more pressing.

headline: Future of Debt Plan; Expectations May Have Been Raised That Turn Out to Be Beyond Reach
abstract: LEAD: There is no quick fix to the developing world's staggering foreign-debt problem, despite the endorsement last week of a new debt-reduction policy by the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.

headline: Taking a Chance on East Europe
abstract: LEAD: A growing number of Western companies in industries ranging from accounting and hotels to copiers and computer software are rushing to invest in the Soviet Union and other Eastern European nations to take advantage of changes in economic policies.

headline: Market Place; Is Paramount Ripe For a Takeover?
abstract: LEAD: WHILE Paramount Communications Inc. concentrates on trying to acquire Time Inc., Wall Street is looking hard at whether Paramount itself could become a takeover target.

headline: Retail Sales Rose 0.4% In April
abstract: LEAD: The nation's retail sales rose four-tenths of 1 percent in April, a smaller rebound from the lackluster trend of the two previous months than economists expected.

headline: Pension Fund Risks Cited
abstract: LEAD: More than $1.6 trillion in pension funds are potentially at risk because of poor regulations and inept enforcement of Federal laws, the Labor Department's Inspector General said today.

headline: Mitterrand Ends a Visit to Bonn Tainted by Kohl's Domestic Woes
abstract: LEAD: President Francois Mitterrand and Chancellor Helmut Kohl today ended a two-day meeting that was colored by the West German leader's sharpening domestic difficulties, which are causing deep concern in Paris.

headline: F.D.A. Official Faces U.S. Charges
abstract: LEAD: Breckinridge L. Willcox, the United States Attorney in Baltimore, filed the first charges yesterday in an investigation of how the Food and Drug Administration approves generic drugs for marketing.

headline: Shandwick Reports Gain in Pretax Profit
abstract: LEAD: Shandwick P.L.C., the publicly held British public relations company whose strategy of growth by acquisition has turned it into one of the largest public relations companies in the world, yesterday released its midyear financial report showing sharp increases in pretax profit.

headline: Chip Futures: Glut of Skepticism
abstract: LEAD: Semiconductor analysts and industry leaders are skeptical about proposals by two stock exchanges to begin trading futures contracts on computer memory chips.

headline: A Rocky Period Lies Ahead For Washington and Beijing
abstract: LEAD: With the hard-liners having emerged in control for the time being in Beijing, the Bush Administration has begun to wrestle with how to relate to a China that is no longer advancing toward more openness but rather toward increased repression.

headline: Author Bows Out of 1990 Peruvian Race
abstract: LEAD: Mario Vargas Llosa, the front-runner in the March 1990 elections and among Latin America's leading writers, announced Wednesday that he is bowing out of the presidential race, blaming political wrangling within the center-right coalition that has been backing him.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Carteret Savings Bank, to Korey, Kay & Partners, with an undisclosed budget.

headline: Japan's New Farm Belt
abstract: LEAD: In California's agricultural belt, a meat-packing plant that had been closed for years reopened recently with new financial backing - Japanese. In the same city, Fresno, a Japanese textile company, is building what will be the first cotton mill west of the Mississippi River.

headline: Now Bilzerian Is Facing the S.E.C.
abstract: LEAD: In one of the largest civil lawsuits accusing a takeover specialist of fraud, the Government today sought $31.3 million in what it said were illegal profits from Paul A. Bilzerian, chairman of the Singer Company.

headline: Stocks Regain Ground, With Dow Up 4.60
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices moved higher yesterday, and the Dow Jones industrial average gained 4.60 points to close at 2,480.15.

headline: Noriega's Foes Say Vote Must Stand
abstract: LEAD: The Panamanian opposition today rejected the Government's decision to annul the presidential election and said it was prepared for talks only if Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega stepped down as military leader.
