headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Account
abstract: LEAD: * Associated Importers Co., to the Bloom Agency, for Suntory beer, with an undisclosed budget.

headline: Business Leaders Take Ad That Backs Milken
abstract: LEAD: A message first seen last year on T-shirts worn by friends and colleagues of Michael Milken appeared yesterday as the headline of a full-page advertisement signed by dozens of prominent business executives: ''Mike Milken, We Believe in You.''

headline: 9th Death in Delhi Rail Blast
abstract: LEAD: A witness to the explosion at a city train station on Monday died today, raising the death toll in the blast to nine. The newest fatality, Kalyan Singh, was a station porter who other witnesses say was handling the luggage that apparently contained a home-made bomb. Police officials had been hoping that Mr.

headline: Walesa Meets Pope for an Emotional Talk
abstract: LEAD: With emotion, and also with a sense of symbolism, Pope John Paul II embraced the Polish labor leader Lech Walesa today and reaffirmed his hope that a new spirit of understanding in Poland would lead to a sweeping transformation of that society.

headline: Study to Cheer Ad Industry
abstract: LEAD: Those who believe in advertising will be heartened by a new report that says advertising gives a greater return on investment than sales promotions. ''We were rather astonished by the results,'' said Alexander L. Biel, executive director of the Ogilvy Center for Research and Development, which compiled the report.

headline: Gorbachev Backs Away From Protest 'Hotheads'
abstract: LEAD: As several hundred thousand disgruntled citizens turned the center of the capital into near-pandemonium tonight, Mikhail S. Gorbachev sharply distanced himself from the unrest that has disrupted his meeting with Chinese leaders.

headline: U.S. Urges Japan to Assume Wider Global Responsibility
abstract: LEAD: The United States said today that Japan should play a bigger political role on the world stage, commensurate with its economic power, and the Bush Administration proposed a new international body to foster economic cooperation in the Pacific Basin.

headline: Market Place; Gold Fields Tests A Complex 'Pill'
abstract: LEAD: OVER the next two weeks, as the biggest takeover battle in British history draws to a close, executives of the world's two largest gold producers, each with a vastly different program, will openly compete for the support of bankers, insurance executives and the managers of other big financial institutions.

headline: Dow Advances 11.38 in 'Witching' Session
abstract: LEAD: Heavy trading related to the ''triple witching hour'' pushed the Dow Jones industrial average up 11.38 points yesterday, to a close of 2,486.38.

headline: Cineplex Officials To Acquire Control
abstract: LEAD: The two top executives of the Cineplex Odeon Corporation, a leading United States and Canadian theater operator and movie production house, will have control of the Toronto-based company after acquiring 7.3 million shares from Charles Bronfman, co-chairman of the Seagram Company.

headline: China Seeks Arrest of Its Top Dissident
abstract: LEAD: The Government issued a warrant today for the arrest of Fang Lizhi, China's best-known dissident, as official press organizations stepped up criticism of the United States.

headline: Code Stolen For Macintosh
abstract: LEAD: Apple Computer Inc. said today that the copyrighted source code for its Macintosh computers had been stolen and illegally distributed through the mail by unknown thieves.

headline: HOUSE, BREAKING WITH BUSH, VOTES CHINA SANCTIONS
abstract: LEAD: House Republicans broke with President Bush and joined Democrats in a vote of 418 to 0 today to impose new sanctions on China and condemn Beijing's suppression of human rights.

headline: Ueberroth Pessimistic On Eastern
abstract: LEAD: Peter V. Ueberroth said last night that he had turned pessimistic about his attempt to buy Eastern Airlines from the Texas Air Corporation.

headline: Hanover Bank Shifts Card Fees and Rates
abstract: LEAD: The Manufacturers Hanover Trust Company, which for years has promoted the low interest rates on its credit cards, is notifying more than three million holders of its cards of new fees recently authorized in New York. For some holders, it is also giving notice of a higher interest rate.

headline: Russians Get Visa Cards
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union's largest bank began issuing Visa cards to replace the passbook savings account, Visa International reported today.

headline: Proxy Fight Set By Union Capital
abstract: LEAD: The Union Capital Corporation and a group of its senior officers, who control a combined 9.9 percent stake in the General Development Corporation, announced a proxy fight for two seats on the 10-member board of the Miami-based real estate concern. Union Capital, a real estate concern based in New York, revealed the plan in a filing with the Securities and Exchange

headline: Excerpts From Bush's News Session
abstract: LEAD: Following are excerpts from President Bush's White House news conference yesterday, as transcribed by the Federal News Service:  OPENING STATEMENT

headline: Holly Farms Sets Conagra Terms
abstract: LEAD: The Holly Farms Corporation said it and Conagra Inc. had set the common stock exchange ratio for their proposed merger at 1.875 Conagra shares for each Holly Farms share. Conagra's shares closed at $32 today, up 12.5 cents, making its offer for Holly Farms worth $60 a share. Tyson Foods Inc. has offered $63.50 a share for Holly Farms.

headline: People
abstract: LEAD: * James B. Cameron and John P. Welsh have been promoted to senior vice presidents at Della Femina McNamee WCRS, Boston.

headline: Control Data Sells Unit to Primerica
abstract: LEAD: The Control Data Corporation, the computer company that recently said it would restructure, sold its Action Data Services unit to the Primerica Corporation. Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Action, with $23.3 million in sales last year, provides data processing and support services to consumer credit companies.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Addendum
abstract: LEAD: * Sommers Rosen Inc., a Philadelphia advertising, marketing and public relations agency, will change its name to Shapson, Gero & Sommers Inc.

headline: Mortgage Rates Are Up
abstract: LEAD: Fixed-rate home mortgages are averaging 11.11 percent, according to a national survey released today by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation. That rate was up from a rate of 11.07 percent last week. On one-year adjustable rate mortgages, lenders were asking an average initial rate of 9.41 percent this week, up from 9.39 percent the week before, Freddie Mac said.

headline: Sudan Rebel to Meet With Officials on Truce
abstract: LEAD: A Sudanese rebel leader said today that he would meet Saturday with members of the Sudanese Government, including the Deputy Prime Minister, to discuss terms of a cease-fire in the six-year-old civil war.

headline: Paramount Seeks to Block Election of 4 Time Directors
abstract: LEAD: Paramount Communications Inc. will ask the Delaware Chancery Court today to void the election of four directors of Time Inc., including J. Richard Munro, Time's chairman and chief executive, and Nicholas J. Nicholas Jr., its president.

headline: Hong Kong Turns Out in Protest Against Its Once and Future Ruler
abstract: LEAD: Braving gale-force winds and drenching rains from Typhoon Brenda, demonstrators turned out by the thousands today in Hong Kong and Macao in support of the Beijing student protests, and against the Chinese Government's hard line.

headline: Time Inc. and Warner Prepare a Counterattack
abstract: LEAD: Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc. are expected to call separate board meetings tomorrow or Wednesday to approve a counterattack on the $10.7 billion hostile takeover offer from Paramount Communications Inc. for Time, people close to both companies said yesterday.

headline: G.E. Profits Rise by 17.1%
abstract: LEAD: The General Electric Company reported today that its first-quarter earnings jumped 17.1 percent from the corresponding period in 1988, in part because of especially strong sales increases in plastic appliances.

headline: Bonn Acts in Iran Chemical-Sale Case
abstract: LEAD: A diplomat at the Iranian Embassy in Bonn, suspected of being a central figure in Iran's efforts to stockpile chemicals used in poison-gas production, is no longer in West Germany, and Bonn has asked that he not return, West German officials said today.

headline: Soviet Census Shows Movement to the Cities
abstract: LEAD: Soviet citizens are increasingly fleeing the farm in search of a better life in already crowded cities, a trend that threatens to worsen the country's economic problems, officials said today.

headline: THE LAWYER OF CHOICE: H. Rodgin Cohen; He's the Counselor Banks Call in a Crisis
abstract: LEAD: Talk with a banker about hostile takeovers and more than likely the first lawyer to be mentioned will be H. Rodgin Cohen, partner at the New York law firm of Sullivan & Cromwell.

headline: VENEZUELA URGES TALKS ON NORIEGA
abstract: LEAD: The President of Venezuela said today that he had asked the Organization of American States to sponsor an emergency meeting of the foreign ministers of all Western Hemisphere countries, to be held in Washington early next week, to seek a diplomatic solution to the deepening crisis in Panama.

headline: Ex-Dictator Favored in Bolivia Election
abstract: LEAD: In 1971, Gen. Hugo Banzer Suarez seized power in Bolivia and ruled for seven years, jailing thousands of opponents and exiling others.

headline: India Reports Successful Test of Mid-Range Missile
abstract: LEAD: India successfully fired its first medium-range surface-to-surface missile today, the Press Trust of India said in a report from the test site on the Bay of Bengal.

headline: Increase in Tool Orders Slowed to 2.9% in March
abstract: LEAD: Orders for American-made machine tools rose 2.9 percent in March from the previous month's level, a rate much slower than the 22.3 percent increase reported for February by the industry's trade association.

headline: China Assails Top Dissident
abstract: LEAD: China's television news said Fang Lizhi, the dissident who took refuge in the United States Embassy, is the real villain in the bloodshed. Page 5.

headline: Tokyo Stocks Climb on Resignation
abstract: LEAD: Investors drove up stock prices markedly in Japan this morning, apparently reacting with relief to the news that Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita had decided to resign rather than endure longer investigations into the Recruit stock scandal.

headline: Fort Howard Planning To Sell Cup Operations
abstract: LEAD: The Fort Howard Corporation, the paper products company that was taken private last year for $3.55 billion, said yesterday that it intended to sell its cup operations.

headline: Nakasone Says He Took Gifts But Asserts, 'I Am Innocent'
abstract: LEAD: In cool but defiant tones, former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone reluctantly faced Parliament today and denied charges that he was a central figure in the influence-peddling scandal that has leveled Japan's political leadership and undercut its new international role.

headline: Global Stock Markets Rose in First Quarter Amid a Few Surprises
abstract: LEAD: The first quarter of 1989 has been marked by some surprises in foreign stock markets.

headline: Upheaval in China; Delay Urged in China Travel; Companies Cautious
abstract: LEAD: The State Department urged yesterday that American citizens defer travel to China for at least 72 hours as a result of the student demonstrations. It also said the United States Embassy had advised travelers in Beijing not to leave their immediate residental area or hotel.

headline: Subroto Sees Strong OPEC
abstract: LEAD: The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will regain much of its former power to control oil prices during the 1990's, but it intends to keep prices stable, its Secretary General, Subroto, said today.

headline: Yields in 5.90% to 7% Range On New York State Bonds
abstract: LEAD: New York State yesterday priced $200.2 million of general obligation bonds through competitive bidding, with Citicorp Securities Markets Inc. the winner.

headline: Turning On the Research Switch
abstract: LEAD: Time was when most companies felt that research and development was something they had to do for themselves and technology developed by others was adopted only as a last resort. However, as international competitive pressures have grown and research has become more expensive, that ''not-invented-here'' syndrome has faded.

headline: Head of Insider Inquiry Is Leaving the S.E.C.
abstract: LEAD: Gary G. Lynch, the lawyer who led the Securities and Exchange Commission's investigation into insider trading and securities fraud on Wall Street, said yesterday that he would leave the agency in mid-July.

headline: Dollar's Rise Keeps Down Rates
abstract: LEAD: Despite some signs of softness, the economy is still growing and the chances of a serious slowdown or recession are remote, a number of analysts contend.

headline: U.S. Businesses Plan Rise Of 6.5% in Capital Spending
abstract: LEAD: American businesses plan a strong 6.5 percent increase in plant and equipment spending this year, the Government said today. Economists said the capital investments would help economic expansion while tending to limit inflation.
